            <outline text="\section{Introduction}% #h "/>
            <outline text="\section{Related Work}% #h ">
                <outline text="Productivity Models in Mathematical Economics}% #h">
                    <outline text="Productivity models in mathematical economics use mathematical frameworks to analyse how inputs like labour, capital, and technology translate into economic output. This section summarises key mathematical models that have been published, from diminishing returns in pre-industrial societies (Malthus) to exogenous innovation in modern growth (Solow). They remain a strong foundation for policy analysis, emphasising the roles of technology and its connection with savings, and sectoral linkages."/>
                    <outline text="Malthusian Model">
                        <outline text="The premise of the model by Malthus [^1] is that population growth outpaces food production, leading to equilibrium where living standards stagnate. The model assumes that food production grows linearly with labour:"/>
                        <outline text="$$Y_t = 1000 + L_t$$."/>
                        <outline text="Population grows quadratically with food surplus:"/>
                        <outline text="$$L_{t+1} = 600 + 100 \left(\frac{Y_t}{L_t}\right)^2$$."/>
                        <outline text="The implications of this are that technological improvements temporarily boost output but are offset by population growth, reinforcing equilibrium."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Solow and Swan">
                        <outline text="The model by Solow and Swan introduces the key equation ">
                            <outline text="$$\dot{k} = s \cdot f(k) - (n + g + \delta)k$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="where $$k$$ is capital per effective labor, $$s$$ is savings rate, $$n$$ is population growth, $$g$$ is technological progress, and $$\delta$$ is depreciation. It predicts that long-term growth depends on exogenous factors like technological progress and defines the residual (Total Factor Productivity, TFP) capturing unexplained output growth from technological or efficiency gains[^2][^6]."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Leontief Input-Output Model">
                        <outline text="The input-output model by Leontief analyses sectoral interdependencies using linear production functions. In matrix form, this can be expressed as">
                            <outline text="$${X} = {AX} + {D}$$,"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="where $${X}$$ is output, $${A}$$ is input coefficients, and $${D}$$ is demand."/>
                        <outline text="A motivating use case for the model is the estimate of ripple effects of demand changes across industries."/>
                        <outline text="[^3][^5]."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Von Neumann Growth Model ">
                        <outline text="The Von Neumann Growth Model uses linear algebra to express growth in an expanding economy based on input and output matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$. The growth and interest rates converge to an equilibrium rate $$\lambda$$ over time. The defining equation">
                            <outline text="$$x({A} - \lambda {B})y = 0$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="has a resemblance to the generalised eigenproblem for linear matrix pencils \cite{Giorno}."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Cobb-Douglas Production Function">
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="- **Formula**: $$Y = A \cdot K^\alpha L^{1-\alpha}$$,"/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="where $$A$$ is TFP, $$K$$ is capital, $$L$$ is labor, and $$\alpha$$ is capital’s output elasticity[^3][^9]."/>
                        <outline text="- **Application**: Links factor inputs to output, showing diminishing returns to capital/labor[^9]."/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Harrod-Domar Model">
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="- **Emphasis**: Savings and investment drive growth[^1]."/>
                        <outline text="- **Equation**: $$S = sY = \sigma \Delta Y$$,"/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="where $$\sigma$$ is the capital-output ratio."/>
                        <outline text="- **Insight**: Higher savings rates ($$s$$) increase capital accumulation and productivity[^1]."/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Modern Productivity Measurements">
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="- **Metrics**:">
                            <outline text="- **Labor Productivity**: $$\frac{Y}{L}$$."/>
                            <outline text="- **Multifactor Productivity (MFP)**: Output relative to combined inputs (weighted average of capital and labor)[^2][^7]."/>
                            <outline text="- **Growth Accounting**: Decomposes output growth into contributions from labor, capital, and TFP[^6][^7]."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text=""/>
                    </outline>
