                    <outline text="Motivation #h ">
                        <outline text="SPECTRAL ANALYSIS OF (NONNEGATIVE) MATRICES &amp;  NONNEGATIVITY PROPERTIES OF EIGENVALUES AND EIGENVECTORS #hh">
                            <outline text="The study of spectral properties of nonnegative matrices is of fundamental importance in linear algebra and its applications [Plemmon]. A particular research field investigates the existence of positive, or more generally non-negative real eigenvectors, following work initiated by Perron [] and Frobenius [], with applications for example in Markov-chains [], Differential-Algebraic Equations (DEAs) [] and game theory [Thompson]. #signpost "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="EXTENSION TO REGULAR PENCILS #hh">
                            <outline text="This theory has been generalised to regular matrix pencils by a number of authors [], most recently in []. "/>
                            <outline text="B INVERTIBLE #hh ">
<outline text="Consider the pencil $$A-\lambda B$$ and assume that $$B$$ is an invertible matrix. Let an eigenvalue $$\mu$$ with eigenvector $$y$$ satisfy">
    <outline text="$$(A-\mu B)y=0 \Leftrightarrow (AB^{-1}-\mu I)z=0$$ where $$z=By$$. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="The problem of computing a pencil eigenvector has thus been reduced to that of computing an eigenvector of the matrix $$AB^{-1}$$. One may then apply the Perron-Frobenius to this matrix in order to obtain specific non-negativity properties of $$\mu$$ and $$z$$. If $$B&gt;0$$, then this matrix is invertible, and the found properties can be "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="B SINGULAR #hh ">
<outline text="The interesting situation arises for $$B\ge 0$$ and more generally $$B$$ singular. "/>
<outline text="DRAZIN #hh ">
    <outline text="An interesting approach, as presented in [], is to consider the Drazin inverse $$B^D$$. If one assumes that $$A$$ and $$B$$ commute, one obtains">
        <outline text="$$(A-\lambda B^DB)y=0 \Rightarrow (AB^{-1}-\lambda I)By=0$$"/>
    </outline>
