<outline text="Definition">
    <outline text="For a regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda LR^\top$$ we define the $$\Lambda$$-matrix as the $$r\times r$$ matrix ">
        <outline text="$$\Lambda=\text{adj}(R\top\text{adj}(A)L)$$.">
            <outline text="$$R\top\text{adj}(A)L\cdot\Lambda=\det(R\top\text{adj}(A)L)\cdot I_r$$ #label:Lambda"/>
            <outline text="$$ \frac{\text{adj}(R\top\text{adj}(A)L)}{\det(R\top\text{adj}(A)L)}\cdot\Lambda=I_r$$. #label:Lambda "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="For different rank-factorisations of $$B$$, we obtain different $$\Lambda$$-matrices but from Remark #label:similar, it can be seen easily that they are related to each other through application of suitable similarity transformations. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Results">
<outline text="**Lemma** If $$\Lambda &gt; 0$$, $$R\top\text{adj}(A)&gt;0$$ and $$\text{adj}(A)L&gt;0$$ then the regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda LR^\top$$ is Frobenius-Perron."/>
<outline text="Proof">
    <outline text="Due to the definition of the $$\Lambda$$-matrix, we have">
        <outline text="$$R\top\text{adj}(A)L\cdot\Lambda=\det(R\top\text{adj}(A)L)\cdot I_r$$ #label:Lambda"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="We will denote $$\mu := \det(R\top\text{adj}(A)L)$$ for ease of notation."/>
    <outline text="Let $$y&gt;0$$ such that $$\Lambda y=\lambda y$$. We will assert that from this, we can derive a positive eigenvector for the pencil #label:the-pencil, for a suitable eigenvalue."/>
    <outline text=" Define $$\tilde{y}=\text{adj}(A)Ly$$. Then we obtain">
        <outline text="$$A \tilde{y}=A\;\text{adj}(A)Ly=\det(A)Ly$$. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Furthermore, using #label:Lambda ">
        <outline text="$$\mu y=R\top\text{adj}(A)L\cdot \Lambda y=R\top\text{adj}(A)L\cdot \lambda y$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Hence, putting this together, ">
        <outline text="$$\mu A \tilde{y}=\det(A)LR\top\text{adj}(A)L\cdot \lambda y=\det(A)\lambda B\tilde{y}\Longleftrightarrow (\mu A-\det(A)\lambda B)\tilde{y}=0$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="We now distinguish three cases:">
        <outline text="(i) Case $$\mu\neq 0, \det(A) \neq 0$$:">
            <outline text="We can see that $$\frac{\det(A)\lambda}{\mu}$$ is a finite nonzero eigenvalue, with positive eigenvector $$\tilde{y}$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="(ii) Case $$\mu = 0, \det(A) \neq 0$$:">
            <outline text="In this case, we can see that $$\tilde{y}$$ is a positive eigenvector for an infinite eigenvalue. "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="(iii) Case $$\mu \neq 0, \det(A) = 0$$:">
            <outline text="Consider $$a \neq 0$$ chosen so that $$\det(A + aLR^\top) \neq 0$$. "/>
            <outline text="[..]"/>
            <outline text="This can be treated by Case (i) for the pencil $$A+ aLR^\top-\lambda LR^\top$$."/>
            <outline text="Finally, we obtain that $$\tilde{y}$$ is a positive eigenvector for the eigenvalue $$0$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="(iv) Case $$\mu = 0, \det(A) = 0$$:"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
