                    <outline text="Abstract #h"/>
                    <outline text="Introduction #h"/>
                    <outline text="Protocol Design #h">
                        <outline text="In this section, we describe a hybrid-entropy stego-distributing architecture, that conforms to the hybrid model defined in section... This architecture is an extension to the work already proposed in @omego2018 and @omego2017, allowing Amara to initiate secretly some banking instruction to the bank and preventing a multi-channel man-in-the-middle attack (MITM)."/>
                        <outline text="Amara wishes to transfer some money to Ebere's account. She shares a secret key $$k$$ with her  bank, which was generated and exchanged during or after the SMS banking registration process. Given some secret banking instruction $$m$$ that Amara will like to instruct to her bank, she will at first generate independently, two faked banking instructions or unsuspicious generic text messages of an arbitrary string $$m_1$$ and $$m_2$$. These text messages are transmitted independently across two wireless mobile channels $$C_1$$ and $$C_2$$. Note that two channels are cover-channels or covers. Amara computes $$m,m_1,m_2$$ and $$k$$ using an $$\mathsf {XOR} (\cdot,\cdot,\cdot,\cdot)$$ functional predicate, to output $$b$$, a random binary value. The binary value with properties of pseudo-random number is encoded using an List-Significant-Bit (LSB) stego-encoding technique, were the output is a stego-object $$(m_3=o)$$. The stego-object $$m_3$$ is transmitted across an insecure auxiliary channel $$C_3$$. On receiving $$m_3$$, the bank decodes $$m_3$$ and extracts $$b$$, then the secret message $$m$$ can be reconstructed. Note that the secret key $$k$$ is not transmitted across any channel. the Hybrid-entropy distributing scheme is summarized in the definition ..."/>
                        <outline text="$$$$\begin{figure} {\footnotesize}"/>
                        <outline text="\centering \[$$$$\begin{array}{c|c|c} \mathrm {Amara} &amp; &amp; \mathrm {Bank} \\ \hline \hline \{ m_1,\,\,m_2,\,m\} &amp; &amp; \\ &amp;  &amp;  \\&amp; \xrightarrow[\quad \quad \quad \text{$$ C_{1}\quad \quad \quad $$}]{\text{$$hello$$ }}\\ &amp; &amp;  N_1 \\ &amp; \xleftarrow[\quad  \quad \quad  \text{$$ C_{1}\quad \quad \quad   $$}]{\text{$$N_1$$ }}  \\ N_{1}||m_1 &amp; &amp; \\  &amp; \xrightarrow[\quad \quad  \quad  \text{$$ C_{1}\quad \quad \quad  $$}]{\text{$$N_{1} || m_1$$ }}\\ &amp; &amp; N_{1}||m_1 \\ &amp; &amp; \\&amp; \\&amp; \xrightarrow[\quad \quad \quad \text{$$ C_{2}\quad \quad \quad $$}]{\text{$$hello$$ }}\\ &amp; &amp; N_2  \\ &amp; \xleftarrow[\quad \quad \quad \text{$$ C_{2}\quad \quad \quad $$}]{\text{$$N_{2}$$ }}\\ N_{2}||m_2 &amp; &amp; \\ &amp; \xrightarrow[\quad \quad \quad \text{$$ C_{2}\quad \quad \quad $$}]{\text{$$N_{2} || m_2$$ }}\\ &amp; &amp;  N_{2}||m_2 \\ &amp; &amp; \\ b=m\oplus m_1\oplus m_2 &amp; &amp; \\ m_3=\textsf{E}(b) &amp; \\ &amp; \xrightarrow[\quad \quad \quad \text{$$ C_{3} \quad \quad \quad $$}]{\text{$$m_3$$ }}\\ &amp; &amp; b=\textsf{D}(m_3)\\&amp; &amp; m = b\oplus m_1\oplus m_2 \end{array}$$$$ \]  \footnotesize {\caption{A Robust Multi-Channel SMS Mobile Banking Protocol}} \label{fig:my_label}$$$$"/>
                        <outline text="\end{figure}"/>
