                    <outline text="Security Analysis #h">
                        <outline text="Steganographic Model #h">
                            <outline text="High-Entropy Steganography #h ">
<outline text="Steganography enables a cover-object with enough entropy to receive a payload (secret message), resulting in a carrier-object (stego-object) (\cite{@Cancelli2007}, \cite{@Memon2001}, \cite{@Alam2013}). This is expressed in the following definition of a high-entropy steganographic system, typical examples of which are the embedding of payload information in multimedia documents (image, video or audio files) or exploiting the redundancy of network protocols such as TCP/IP:"/>
<outline text="Definition #definition:high-entropy">
    <outline text="A __high-entropy steganographic system__ $$\mathcal S_{h}$$ consists of three efficient algorithms: a probabilistic key generator $$\mathsf{Gen}(\cdot)$$, a probabilistic function $$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot, \cdot, \cdot)$$ and a deterministic function $$\mathsf {Dec}(\cdot, \cdot).$$  ">
        <outline text="$$\mathsf{Gen}$$ takes as input a security parameter $$1^k \leftarrow \mathsf {Gen} (1^n)$$ and returns a key (the __stego-key__) $$k$$."/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot, \cdot, \cdot)$$ is the steganographic embedding function that receives the secret message $$m$$ (payload) and a cover-object $$c$$, returning a carrier-object $$o$$."/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf {Dec}(\cdot, \cdot)$$ is a deterministic algorithm that returns the embedded secret message (payload) $$m$$  by extracting it from the carrier-medium."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="For all messages $$m$$ of size bounded by a polynomial in the size of the cover medium, the following condition holds: $$\mathsf {Dec}(k, \mathsf{Enc}(k,c,m))=m$$."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Low-Entropy Steganography #h ">
<outline text="However, if a cover-object lacks enough entropy to conceal a secret message, a low-entropy steganographic model can be employed. This model is formalised in the following"/>
<outline text="Definition #definition:low-entropy ">
    <outline text="A __low-entropy steganographic system__ $$\mathcal{S}_{l}$$ consists of three efficient algorithms as in the high-entropy model, but with a number of differences relating to the arguments of the embedding function and its inverse. ">
        <outline text="The embedding function $$\mathsf {Enc}$$ returns a stego-object $$o$$ and additionally a secret message $$m'$$ (which may be identical to $$m$$). "/>
        <outline text=" As a result, $$\mathsf {Dec}$$ has $$m'$$ as an additional input parameter."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The following property now holds for all messages $$m$$ irrespective of their size: if $$(o,m')=\mathsf {Enc}(k,c,m)$$, then $$\mathsf {Dec}(k,o,m')=m$$."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Hybrid-Entropy Steganography  #h ">
<outline text="The steganographic protocol presented in the previous section combines both low-entropy and high-entropy steganography."/>
<outline text=" In order to evaluate its security, we define a hybrid security model."/>
<outline text="We present a formal notion of security in our stego SMS based banking model."/>
<outline text=" The notion aims to describe a generic definition that combines both low-entropy and high-entropy steganographic systems."/>
<outline text="Definition #definition:hybrid-entropy ">
    <outline text="A Hybrid-Entropy steganography system $$\mathcal S$$, is considered a combination of both high-entropy $$\mathcal {S}^{h}$$ and a low-entropy stego-system $$\mathcal {S}^{l}$$, that consists of three efficient algorithms and a bi-conditional function."/>
    <outline text="several stego subsystems"/>
    <outline text="at least one low and one high"/>
    <outline text="typically: several communication channels and interaction between payloads"/>
    <outline text="INBOX">
        <outline text="The three efficient algorithms consists of $$\mathsf {Gen}(\cdot)$$, $$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot, \cdot)$$, $$\mathsf {Dec}(\cdot,\cdot)$$  and $$\mathsf {XOR} (\oplus)$$."/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf {Gen}(\lambda):$$ is a deterministic algorithm that, takes as an input a security parameter $$\lambda$$ and returns on outputs  $$k \in \{0,1\} \, \leftarrow \sf{Gen}(\lambda)$$."/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot,\cdot):$$ Given a secret banking instruction $$m \in \mathcal {M}$$, pick two faked banking instructions $$m_1$$ and $$m_2$$ independently of the secret and publish them to $${C}_{i}\in \mathcal{C^l}(i=1,2)$$ respectively."/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf {XOR} (\cdot, \cdot, \cdot):$$ is both a deterministic and a bi-conditional function that takes as an input $$\,m_1, \, m_2 ,  m , k$$ and returns $$b \in \{0,1\}$$ as an output, such that $$\,|m_1|\equiv|m_2|,|m|\equiv|m_2|$$ and $$|m_2|\equiv|k|$$."/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot,\cdot):$$ is a probabilistic encoding algorithm that takes as an input a stego-cover $$c$$ and $$b$$, returns a stego-object $$o \in \mathcal {O}^h$$ as an output. It should hold that:$$$$o= \mathsf {Enc}(c,b)$$$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf{Dec}(\cdot,\cdot):$$ is a deterministic decoding algorithm that takes as an input a stego-object $$o$$ and a symmetric key $$k$$ and returns an output $$b$$:$$$$b=\mathsf {Dec}(o,k)$$$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Formal Security Definition #h ">
                            <outline text="We now formalize the notion of steganographic security. We aim to provide a generic definition that applies to both high- and low-entropy stego-systems, thus, we start by defining the general notation for a stego-system."/>
                            <outline text="Definition #definition:stego-system">
<outline text="A __steganographic system__ $$\mathcal S$$ is either a high-entropy steganographic system $$\mathcal S_h$$ or a low-entropy steganographic system $$\mathcal S_l$$. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="To simplify notations, let $$o(m)$$ denote a cover object that simply encodes the message $$m$$. Thus, in a high-entropy steganographic system $$o(m) =\mathsf{Enc}(k, c,m)$$, and in a low-entropy steganographic system we have $$(o(m),m')$$ = $$\mathsf{Enc}(k, c,m)) $$."/>
                            <outline text="Before defining the notion of a secure steganographic system $$\mathcal S$$, we introduce the Indistinguishability Game 1, a non-cooperative sequential two-player game between an adversary $$\mathsf {A}$$ and a challenger $$\mathsf {Ch}$$. The adversary $$\mathsf {A}$$ is given a limited access to an probabilistic oracle $$\mathsf O$$ that returns a set of steganographic cover objects $$\{c_1, c_2. . . , c_n\}$$. These cover objects are taken from the set suitable for the type of steganographic system, i.e., $$\mathcal C_h$$ for a high-entropy and $$\mathcal C_l$$ for a low-entropy steganographic system."/>
                            <outline text="This game proceeds as follows:"/>
                            <outline text="Game 1 $$\big(\mathsf{IND-STEGO} (\mathsf{Adv},\mathsf{Ch},\mathsf S,\kappa) \big)$$  #label:Ind-Stego ">
<outline text="1) The adversary $$\mathsf {A}$$ outputs a message $$m$$."/>
<outline text="2) The challenger $$\mathsf {Ch}$$ returns either $$o' = \mathsf {Enc}(c, m)$$ or a pseudo(?)random stego-object $$o'$$ with probability $$p=\frac{1}{2}$$."/>
<outline text="3) $$\mathsf A$$ might perform a certain number of calculations that is polynomial in $$\kappa$$ . Finally $$\mathsf {A}$$ selects and outputs a bit $$b \in \{0,1\}$$ uniformly at pseudo-random, where $$b = 1$$ if $$\mathsf {A}$$ believes that $$o' = \mathsf {Enc}(c, m)$$ and $$b = 0$$ otherwise."/>
<outline text="Suppose $$\mathsf {A}$$ could successfully guess the type of object returned by $$\mathsf {Ch}$$, then the game outputs $$1$$ if the condition holds: $$(o' = \mathsf {Enc}(c, m) ∧ b = 1) ∨ (o' \neq \mathsf {Enc}(c, m) ∧ b = 0),$$ i.e."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="We now define $$\mathsf{IND-STEGO}$$ security using Game 1 above: ">
<outline text="Definition #definition:stego-security">
    <outline text="A stego-system $$\mathcal S$$ is IND-STEGO-secure if there exists a negligible function $$\mathsf {negl}$$ such that, for any probabilistic polynomial time adversary $$\mathsf {Adv}$$, it holds that:"/>
    <outline text="$$\mathsf{Pr}\big(\mathsf {IND-STEGO}(\mathsf{Adv},\mathsf{Ch},\mathsf S,\kappa)  = 1\big) ≤ \dfrac{1}{2} +\mathsf {negl}(κ)$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Definition 4b [@ref]">
    <outline text="A steganographic system $$\mathcal S \mapsto \prod=(\mathsf {Gen}, \mathsf{Enc}, \mathsf {Dec})$$ is indistinguishable under a chosen covert-text attack if, an adversary $$\sf A$$ is bounded within a probabilistic polynomial time algorithm and an arbitrary message $$m$$, it should hold that $$\mathsf {Prob} \Big ( \sf {A} \big(\mathbb S, \mathsf {Enc}(m) \big)=1 \Big ) \leq \dfrac{1}{2} + \epsilon(n)$$where $$\epsilon$$ is a negligible function."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Security Proof for Low-Entropy Stego-System #h ">
                            <outline text="Security Analysis As mentioned earlier, our proposed scheme is an example of a low-entropy stego-system. We now prove that it is **IND-STEGO-**secure, by measuring the advantage an adversary Adv has in wining the **IND-STEGO-**game. We consider two different adversaries (defined in Section II): the Online social network adversary and the Internet Provider adversary."/>
                            <outline text="Online Social Network. ">
<outline text="Without loss of generality we will use Facebook as an example of a social network adversary. Facebook has the ability to read any message posted by any user as well as monitor user behavior. "/>
<outline text="Even though Facebook has full access to the short text $$t_A$$, there is no way to check if $$t_A$$ corresponds to any secret information, since $$t_A$$ is specifically chosen independently of the secret. The short text need not have any specific structure or be about any specific topic. In fact, $$t_A$$ could be a text that Alice would have posted anyway and therefore it is indistinguishable from any other message in $$\mathcal C^∗$$, in fact Facebook does not even know which server a potential secret is stored on, since this information is part of the key. This means that Facebook can only win the IND-STEGO-game with probability 1/2, and the scheme is thus IND-STEGO-secure under a social network adversary."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Internet Provider. ">
<outline text="The Internet Provider adversary is assumed to have all the powers of the social media plus the ability to monitor all connections of specific users in their jurisdiction. "/>
<outline text="First, we observe that if none of the parties involved in the protocol (other than Facebook) are under observation the analysis is identical to the social media scenario, and the scheme is IND-STEGO-secure. "/>
<outline text="If at least one other party is under observation, we need a more careful analysis. Without loss of generality we assume that Alice is the one under observation. The adversary (**Adv**) will see that Alice connected to the storage server, i.e, **Adv** will know $$srv$$, which is part of the key. **Adv** can try to use this knowledge to get an advantage in the IND-STEGO-game."/>
<outline text="The IND-STEGO-game proceeds according to Game 1 as follows. (1) **Adv** has access to all the users previous messages (as well as any arbitrary message). (2) **Adv** submits a secret message $$m_{Adv}$$ to $$Ch$$ and $$Ch$$ must now return a stego-object. This involves computing the MAC of an independently chosen short text $$t_{Ch}$$, to obtain a username and password, then upload a secret (either $$m_{Adv}$$ or random data, chosen with probability 1/2) to the storage server $$srv$$, and make the secret accessible using the newly created username and password. After that the stego-object $$t_{Ch}$$ is returned to Adv. (3) Adv must now guess if the secret on the storage server is $$m_{Adv}$$ or not."/>
<outline text="Having $$A$$ under observation, **Adv** knows the location of the storage server $$srv$$, but assuming the connection between $$A$$ and $$srv$$ is secure, **Adv** learns nothing about the data exchanged between $$A$$ and $$srv$$. **Adv** learns nothing by supplying an incorrect username and password to the storage server, and **Adv** cannot create the username and password without knowledge of the MAC-key. Guessing the username and password corresponds to guessing the output of the MAC, which can only be done with probability $$1/2^n$$, where n is the number of bits of the MAC output. Since $$1/2^n$$ is negligible the protocol is IND-STEGO-secure."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Steganographic Model #h">
                            <outline text="#signpost "/>
                            <outline text="In contrast to encryption, undetectability remains the main purpose of steganography,i.e; the science of communicating covert message in a manner that is undetectable by unauthorised persons, apart from the sender and the intended recipients. Various studies has been enormously on steganography: In this section, we review various studies relevant to steganography in mobile banking "/>
                            <outline text="Researchers such as \cite{@Christian1998}, \cite{@Zollner1998} and \cite{@Thomas1999} have focused on theoretical definitions of steganography. \cite{@Christian1998} proposed steganographic definitions and adversarial games for steganography. The security of the stego-system presented is in terms of the relative entropy between the distribution of the stego-text and the cover-text. \cite{@Thomas1999} described a model which includes a characterization and definitions of two critical components of a steganographic system, the encoding process and the adversaries attack on the stego-object. The definition of the two components is based on a requirement in the maximum distortion between cover-object, stego-object and the modified stego-object. In \cite{@Zollner1998}, model which enables evaluation of a stego-system's security against a known plain-text is presented. "/>
                            <outline text="Studies in \cite{@katzenbeisser2002} and \cite{@Hopper2002} presented formal definition and theoretical structures, based on cipher based computational indistinguishability. \cite{@katzenbeisser2002} provided definitions that reply on a probabilistic game, were an adversary is faced with a steganographic decision problem, while \cite{@Hopper2002} uses cryptographic and complexity-theory proof methods to described conditions necessary of a secure stego-system. "/>
                            <outline text="@Beato2014 "/>
                            <outline text="High-Entropy Steganography #h">
<outline text="Steganography enables a cover-object with enough entropy to contain a secret message (\cite{@Cancelli2007}, \cite{@Memon2001}, \cite{@Alam2013}). This is expressed in the following definition of a high-entropy steganogrpahic-system:"/>
<outline text="Definition 1}: A high-entropy steganographic-system $$\mathbb S_{H}$$ incorporates three efficient algorithms: a probabilistic key generator $$\mathsf{Gen}(\cdot)$$, a probabilistic function $$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot, \cdot, \cdot)$$ and a deterministic function $$\mathsf {Dec}(\cdot, \cdot).$$  ">
    <outline text="$$\mathsf{Gen}$$ takes as input a security parameter $$1^k \leftarrow \mathsf {Gen} (1^n)$$ and returns a (stego- key in most cases) key $$k$$ -- in our steganographic system, encryption is not actually required however its use would make it difficult for an adversary have access to a payload, and hence further increase the security of the protocol."/>
    <outline text="$$\mathsf {Enc}(\cdot, \cdot, \cdot)$$ is the steganographic embedding function that receives the secret message $$m$$ (payload) and a cover-object $$c$$, returning a carrier-object $$o$$."/>
    <outline text="$$\mathsf {Dec}(\cdot, \cdot)$$ is a deterministic algorithm that returns the embedded secret message (payload) $$m$$  by extracting it from the carrier-medium."/>
</outline>
<outline text="For all messages $$m$$ of size bounded by a polynomial in the size of the cover medium, the following condition holds: $$\mathsf {Dec}(k, \mathsf{Enc}(k,c,m))=m$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Low-Entropy Steganography #h">
<outline text="However, if a cover-object lacks enough entropy to conceal a secret message, then a low entropy steganographic model can be utilized. \textit{Definition 2} formalizes the low entropy steganographic model."/>
<outline text="Definition 2 (Low Entropy System)"/>
<outline text="A low-entropy steganographic system $$\mathbb{S}_{L}$$ consists of three efficient algorithms as in the high-entropy model but with a number of differences:">
    <outline text="The embedding function $$\mathsf {Enc}$$ returns a stego-object $$o$$ and additionally a secret message $$m'$$ (which may be identical to $$m$$). "/>
    <outline text=" As a result, $$\mathsf {Dec}$$ has $$m'$$ as an additional input parameter."/>
</outline>
<outline text="The following property now holds for all messages $$m$$ irrespective of their size: if $$(o,m')=\mathsf {Enc}(k,c,m)$$, then $$\mathsf {Dec}(k,o,m')=m$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Formal Security Definition #h">
<outline text="We now formalize the notion of steganographic security. We aim to provide a generic definition that applies to both high- and low-entropy stego-systems, thus, we start by defining the general notation for a stego-system."/>
<outline text="Definition 3 (Steganographic-system): A steganographic system $$\mathbb S$$ is either a high-entropy steganographic system $$S_h$$ or a low-entropy steganographic-system $$S_l$$. "/>
<outline text="To simplify the notation, let $$o(m)$$ denote a cover object that simply encodes the message $$m$$. Then, in a high-entropy steganographic system $$o(m) =\mathsf{Enc}(k, c,m)$$, and in a low-entropy steganographic-system we have $$(o(m),m')$$ = $$\mathsf{Enc}(k, c,m)) .$$"/>
<outline text="Before presenting our notion of a secure steganographic system $$\mathbb S$$, we introduce Game 1, a game played between an adversary and a challenger."/>
<outline text="The game between an adversary $$\mathsf {A}$$ and a challenger $$\mathsf {Ch}$$ proceeds as follows:"/>
<outline text="Game 1 $$\big(\mathsf{IND-STEGO}_{\mathsf{Adv},\mathsf{Ch},\mathbb S}(\kappa) \big)$$ #game ">
    <outline text="1) An adversary $$\mathsf {A}$$ is given a limited access to an probabilistic oracle $$\mathsf O$$ that returns a set of steganographic cover objects $$\{c_1, c_2. . . , c_n\}$$. These cover objects are taken from the set suitable for the type of steganographic system, i.e., $$\mathcal C_h$$ for a high-entropy steganographic system and $$\mathcal C_l$$ for a low-entropy steganographic system."/>
    <outline text="2) The adversary $$\mathsf {A}$$ outputs a message $$m$$ and the challenger $$\mathsf {Ch}$$ returns either $$o' = \mathsf {Enc}(c, m)$$ or a pseudorandom stego-object $$o'$$ with probability $$\dfrac{1}{2}$$."/>
    <outline text="3) $$\mathsf A$$ might perform a certain number of calculations that is polynomial in $$\kappa$$ ."/>
    <outline text="4) Eventually, $$\mathsf {A}$$ selects and outputs a bit $$b \in \{0,1\}$$ uniformly at pseudo-random, where $$b = 1$$ if $$\mathsf {A}$$ believes that $$o' = \mathsf {Enc}(c, m) ∧ b = 0$$ otherwise."/>
    <outline text="5) Suppose $$\mathsf {A}$$ could successfully guess the type of object returned by $$\mathsf {Ch}$$, then the game outputs $$1$$ if the condition holds:$$(o' = \mathsf {Enc}(c, m) ∧ b = 1) ∨ (o' \neq \mathsf {Enc}(c, m) ∧ b = 0),$$ i.e."/>
</outline>
<outline text="We now define $$\mathsf{IND-STEGO}$$ security using Game 1 above: ">
    <outline text="Definition 4a">
        <outline text="A stego-system $$\mathbb S$$ is IND-STEGO-secure if there exists a negligible function $$\mathsf {negl}$$ such that, for any probabilistic polynomial time adversary $$\mathsf {Adv}$$, it holds that:"/>
        <outline text="$$\mathsf{Pr}\big(\mathsf {IND-STEGO}_{\mathsf {Adv},\mathsf {Ch},\mathbb{S}}(κ) = 1\big) ≤ \dfrac{1}{2} +\mathsf {negl}(κ)$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Definition 4b [@ref]">
        <outline text="A steganographic system $$\mathbb S \mapsto \prod=(\mathsf {Gen}, \mathsf{Enc}, \mathsf {Dec})$$ is indistinguishable under a chosen covert-text attack if, an adversary $$\sf A$$ is bounded within a probabilistic polynomial time algorithm and an arbitrary message $$m$$, it should hold that $$\mathsf {Prob} \Big ( \sf {A} \big(\mathbb S, \mathsf {Enc}(m) \big)=1 \Big ) \leq \dfrac{1}{2} + \epsilon(n)$$where $$\epsilon$$ is a negligible function."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Proof of Security: Low-Entropy Stego-System #h">
<outline text="Security Analysis As mentioned earlier, our proposed scheme is an example of a low-entropy stego-system. We now prove that it is **IND-STEGO-**secure, by measuring the advantage an adversary Adv has in wining the **IND-STEGO-**game. We consider two different adversaries (defined in Section II): the Online social network adversary and the Internet Provider adversary."/>
<outline text="Online Social Network. ">
    <outline text="Without loss of generality we will use Facebook as an example of a social network adversary. Facebook has the ability to read any message posted by any user as well as monitor user behavior. "/>
    <outline text="Even though Facebook has full access to the short text $$t_A$$, there is no way to check if $$t_A$$ corresponds to any secret information, since $$t_A$$ is specifically chosen independently of the secret. The short text need not have any specific structure or be about any specific topic. In fact, $$t_A$$ could be a text that Alice would have posted anyway and therefore it is indistinguishable from any other message in $$\mathcal C^∗$$, in fact Facebook does not even know which server a potential secret is stored on, since this information is part of the key. This means that Facebook can only win the IND-STEGO-game with probability 1/2, and the scheme is thus IND-STEGO-secure under a social network adversary."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Internet Provider. ">
    <outline text="The Internet Provider adversary is assumed to have all the powers of the social media plus the ability to monitor all connections of specific users in their jurisdiction. "/>
    <outline text="First, we observe that if none of the parties involved in the protocol (other than Facebook) are under observation the analysis is identical to the social media scenario, and the scheme is IND-STEGO-secure. "/>
    <outline text="If at least one other party is under observation, we need a more careful analysis. Without loss of generality we assume that Alice is the one under observation. The adversary (**Adv**) will see that Alice connected to the storage server, i.e, **Adv** will know $$srv$$, which is part of the key. **Adv** can try to use this knowledge to get an advantage in the IND-STEGO-game."/>
    <outline text="The IND-STEGO-game proceeds according to Game 1 as follows. (1) **Adv** has access to all the users previous messages (as well as any arbitrary message). (2) **Adv** submits a secret message $$m_{Adv}$$ to $$Ch$$ and $$Ch$$ must now return a stego-object. This involves computing the MAC of an independently chosen short text $$t_{Ch}$$, to obtain a username and password, then upload a secret (either $$m_{Adv}$$ or random data, chosen with probability 1/2) to the storage server $$srv$$, and make the secret accessible using the newly created username and password. After that the stego-object $$t_{Ch}$$ is returned to Adv. (3) Adv must now guess if the secret on the storage server is $$m_{Adv}$$ or not."/>
    <outline text="Having $$A$$ under observation, **Adv** knows the location of the storage server $$srv$$, but assuming the connection between $$A$$ and $$srv$$ is secure, **Adv** learns nothing about the data exchanged between $$A$$ and $$srv$$. **Adv** learns nothing by supplying an incorrect username and password to the storage server, and **Adv** cannot create the username and password without knowledge of the MAC-key. Guessing the username and password corresponds to guessing the output of the MAC, which can only be done with probability $$1/2^n$$, where n is the number of bits of the MAC output. Since $$1/2^n$$ is negligible the protocol is IND-STEGO-secure."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="STEGO INBOX">
<outline text="Researchers has made efforts by proposing several steganographic methods using images as stego-covers, many of which utilize the Least Significant Bit (LSB) to reduce significant changes in the stego-cover in order to prevent suspicion. Methods proposed in studies such as \cite{@Franz1999}, \cite{@Roque2009} and [] use the LSB technique to conceal secret messages. The F5 steganographic algorithm proposed in \cite{@Westfeld2001} foolows the orthodox steganographic approach. The study in \cite{@Westfeld2000} shows that the F5 algorithm is resilient to statistical and visual attacks. Subsequent study in \cite{@Roque2009} proposed a new image based steganographic algorithm, Selected Least Significant Bit (LSB) by improving the spatial domain of LSB hiding. "/>
<outline text="\cite{@Mathkour2008} proposed a steganogaphic technique that uses a specific method which prevents images downgrading, this makes the stego-object secure against all possible statistical and visual attacks. However, the security of this approach is achieved by using an encryption algorithm. An Unconventional in \cite{@Changescyclic2012} uses X-Box mapping and LSB to conceal secrets in an image. Without knowledge of the mapping rules, extracting the secrets data is difficult."/>
                            </outline>
