                <outline text="A Game-Theoretic Framework for Human-Assisted Sensing and Learning" _note="#slide #h #signpost #moomin ">
                    <outline text="Abstract #h1 ">
                        <outline text="In this paper, contributions to game theory and security games are made. Furthermore, an application to adversarial learning is presented.  #signpost " complete="true"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Introduction #h1 ">
                        <outline text="#signpost "/>
                        <outline text="Contributions #h2">
                            <outline text="The first contribution of this paper is purely game-theoretic, showing that the linear algebra concept of generalised eigensystems can be used for the Nash equilibrium analysis of non-zero sum games. This extends existing results from matrix to bimatrix games and will be the main tool for analysing games throughout this paper. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                            <outline text="The second is a contribution to security games with a formulation of a Bayesian non-zero sum two-player security game and its equilibrium analysis. The design of the game is informed by a systematic and complete classification of 2x2 bimatrix security games, capturing aspects of trust, non-cooperation and unreliability between the machine and a human Wizard. #signpost " complete="true">
<outline text="It is suggested that this may serve as a reference game as it is both generic enough to .. and based on a ... #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="The analysis is generic enough to be used as a framework for other, more specific security games. "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The third contribution is the application of our results to a specific AL game whose payoff functions are informed by a real ML scenario. A simulation and evaluation illustrates the advantages of the game theoretic approach. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Notations #h2 ">
                            <outline text="We fix some notations that will be used in the remainder of the paper. "/>
                            <outline text="Denote $$A, B$$ square, real matrices of dimension $$n&gt;1$$. Furthermore, $$x$$ will be a real row and $$y$$ a real column vector. We frequently require $$e$$, a column vector consisting only of entry 1 and $$E$$ an square matrix with all entries set to 1. The dimensions of $$x$$, $$y$$, $$e$$ and $$E$$ which will be clear from the context. "/>
                            <outline text="A __matrix pencil__ is an expression of the form $$A-\lambda B$$ where $$\lambda$$ is an indeterminate. The matrix pencil $$A-\lambda B$$ is a __regular__ matrix pencil if the matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$ are square and $$\det(A-\lambda^* B)  \neq 0$$ for all but a finite number of values of $$\lambda^*$$. Otherwise, it is referred to as __singular__. "/>
                            <outline text="A __finite generalised eigenvalue__  $$\lambda^*$$ of a regular matrix pencil is a real number for which the determinant  $$\det(A-\lambda^* B)$$ vanishes. The __left__ and __right generalised eigenvectors__ with respect to $$\lambda^*$$ are then solutions of the equations $$x(A-\lambda^* B)=0$$ and $$(A-\lambda^* B)y=0$$ respectively, where $$\lambda^*$$ is a generalised eigenvalue. Note that such numbers $$\lambda^*$$ do not necessarily have to exist, and hence not every regular matrix pencil possesses finite generalised eigenvalues and eigenvectors. More information about matrix pencils can be found for example in #ref:@Gantmacher. "/>
                            <outline text="We will be interested in matrices of the form $$A-\lambda = ((a_{ij}-\lambda))$$. Our preferred notation for these will be matrix pencil representation of the form $$A-\lambda E$$ where $$E$$ is defined as previously. It can be seen that for matrix pencils of this special form, under the assumption of regularity, there exists at the most one finite generalised real eigenvalue, with one corresponding left and right generalised eigenvector. "/>
                            <outline text="In this case, the collection $${\mathcal E}_{A}=(\lambda^*,x,y)$$ of the generalised eigenvalue (if it exists), left and right eigenvectors  will be referred to as the __generalised eigensystem__ associated with the regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda E$$. "/>
                            <outline text="A __bimatrix game__ is a two-person, non-zero sum static game $$G=(X,Y,A,B)$$ where $$X$$ and $$Y$$ are the sets of strategies for the different players, $$A:X\times Y \mapsto \mathbb{R}$$ is the payoff function for Player 1 and $$B:X\times Y \mapsto \mathbb{R}$$ is the payoff function for Player 2. The first player plays a row action whereas the second player plays a column action. An action is contained in a strategy, which can be pure or mixed. The latter is expressed as a pair of probability vectors $$x,y \in {\mathbb R}^n$$ with $$0\le x_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i x_i=1$$ and $$0\le y_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i y_i=1$$."/>
                            <outline text="A __Nash Equilibrium__ $$(x^*,y^*)$$ of the game $$G$$ satisfies $$ x^*Ay^* \ge  xAy^* \;\forall x,\; x^*By^* \ge    x^*By\;\forall y$$. Then, $$v=(v_A,v_B)$$ where $$v_A = x^*Ay^*$$ and $$v_B = x^*By^*$$ is called an __equilibrium value pair__ of the bimatrix game $$G$$ and $$x^*,y^*$$ are Nash Equilibrium (NE) strategies. NE strategies may be pure or mixed, and the corresponding NE is referred to as a pure or mixed NE. "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Bimatrix Games and Generalised Eigensystems #h1 ">
                        <outline text="We introduce the linear algebra framework for analysing certain classes of bimatrix games in this section. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                        <outline text="Fundamental Theorem #h2 #moomin ">
                            <outline text="In this section, specialising the work of \cite{Thompson1971} to matrix games, we extend their main fundamental result to bimatrix games.  #signpost " complete="true"/>
                            <outline text="Given a square bimatrix game $$G(A,B)$$, assume the matrix pencils $$A-\lambda E$$  and $$B-\lambda E$$ are both regular, each with a real eigenvalue $$\mu_A$$ and $$\mu_B$$ respectively. Let $$x_{\mu_B}$$ be a left eigenvector of $$B-\lambda E$$ with respect to $$\mu_B$$ and denote $$y_{\mu_A}$$ a right eigenvector of $$A-\lambda E$$ with respect to $$\mu_A$$. Assume that both $$x_{\mu_B}$$ and $$y_{\mu_A}$$ are nonnegative. Then $$(x^*,y^*) = (x_{\mu_B}$$, $$y_{\mu_A}$$) is a Nash Equilibrium strategy of the game $$G$$ and $$v=(\mu_A, \mu_B)$$ is the corresponding game value pair. #eyo-style:Theorem  #theorem:bimatrix-regular-theorem #novel" _note="https://dynalist.io/d/F6qJJul5x4JWwZ4KTrIffFqu#z=wCoCENOW7xbnwil1r7B1NOr2"/>
                            <outline text="The proof of the theorem will be aided by the following lemma. It exhibits a special case arising where there exists a strategy of one player to which any strategy of the other player is a best response."/>
                            <outline text="Following the notations as in the theorem, we have for a nonnegative left generalised eigenvector $$x_{\mu_B}$$ that for all Player 2 strategies $$y$$ it holds $$x_{\mu_B} B y = \mu_B $$. Similarly, a nonnegative right eigenvector $$y_{\mu_A}$$ satisfies $$x A y_{\mu_A} = \mu_A$$ for all Player 1 strategies $$x$$. #eyo-style:Lemma  #lemma:best-response-eigen" _note="https://dynalist.io/d/F6qJJul5x4JWwZ4KTrIffFqu#z=3m3Y6iQlnd3hELxHkQr40trZ"/>
                            <outline text="#eyo-style:Proof ">
<outline text="Assume that $$x^{\top}_{\mu_A}\ge 0$$ is a left eigenvector, associated with the eigenvalue $${\mu_A}$$ of the regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda E$$. This implies"/>
<outline text="#equation:left-nullspace-eq">
    <outline text=" $$ x^{\top}_{\mu_A}(A-{\mu_A} E)=0. $$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Due to the normalisation property $$\sum x_{{\mu_A},i}=1$$ we have $$ x^{\top}_{\mu_A} E = x^{\top}_{\mu_A} ee^{\top}=e^{\top}$$ so that equation #ref:left-nullspace-eq implies ">
    <outline text="$$ x^{\top}_{\mu_A} A = {\mu_A} e^{\top}$$.  #displaymaths "/>
</outline>
<outline text="The second property for a right eigenvector $$y_{\mu_B}$$ can be shown similarly. From this, the lemma follows. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Proof [of Theorem #ref:bimatrix-regular-theorem ] " complete="true">
<outline text="Let $$y_{\mu_A}$$ be nonnegative right eigenvector of $$A-\lambda E$$ with respect to the eigenvalue $$\mu_A$$. From Lemma #ref:best-response-lemma we deduce that $$y_{\mu_A}$$ is a best response to any Player 1 strategy $$x$$, in particular to  $$x=x_{\mu_B}$$. Likewise,  denote $$x_{\mu_B}$$ a nonnegative left generalised eigenvector of $$B-\lambda E$$. We obtain that  $$x_{\mu_B}$$ is a best response to Player 2 strategy $$y=y_{\mu_A}$$. Hence these strategies are mutual best responses and by definition mixed Nash Equilibrium strategies with payoffs $$\mu_A$$ and $$\mu_B$$ as required. #proof "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Related Work #h2 ">
                            <outline text="In this section, we review work concerned with the use of generalised eigensystems for game theory. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                            <outline text="The results developed in the previous sections are building on several published papers, some of them part of early research in game theory. The aim of this section is to review these papers by summarising their main contributions and relating them to the results of this paper. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="In this section, we introduce the classification of 2x2 bimatrix security games and derive the algebraic framework for analysing and solving these games. This will then be used for the formulation of a Bayesian non-zero sum two-player AL game and its equilibrium analysis. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="And now the repeated game....."/>
                    <outline text="Application to Adversarial Learning #h1 ">
                        <outline text="In this section, we present an application to machine learning, based on our previous game-theoretical results. #signpost " complete="true"/>
                        <outline text="Underlying System Model #h ">
                            <outline text="The System Model #slide  ">
<outline text="![system.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/y44jozn7suoojs1/system.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Machine Component #slide ">
<outline text="For the ML component denote">
    <outline text="$$c$$ -- running cost"/>
    <outline text="$$R$$ -- reliability (probability of correct classification)"/>
    <outline text="$$b$$ -- benefit (assume proportional to its reliability)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="The component's utility is then $$u = c-b=c-\alpha R$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Wizard Component #slide ">
<outline text="Similarly, for this component we have">
    <outline text="$$c_W \gg c $$ -- running cost (typically)"/>
    <outline text="$$R_W \gg R $$ -- reliability (ideally!)"/>
    <outline text="$$b_W$$ -- benefit"/>
</outline>
<outline text="We state $$u_W= c_W-b_W=c_W-\beta R_W$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="System Utility #slide #wfe-ignore-outline ">
<outline text="The overall system reliability (using the first $$k$$ ML components) is ">
    <outline text="$$R_S = \left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1-\prod_k(1-R_i), &amp;\text{ if Wizard is not used.}\\ R_W, &amp;\text{ otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="The system overall utility can be stated as">
    <outline text="$$U_S= \left\{\begin{array}{ll} \alpha R_S - \sum_k c_i, &amp;\text{ if Wizard is not used.}\\ \alpha R_W- c_W, &amp;\text{ otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Potential goals: ">
    <outline text="maximise $$R_S$$?"/>
    <outline text="maximise $$U_S$$?"/>
    <outline text="maximise $$U_S$$ and ensure $$R_S \ge t$$ where $$t$$ is a given threshold?"/>
</outline>
<outline text="We seem to need some mathematical optimisation technique here."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
