                    <outline text="Introduction">
                        <outline text="CONTEXT">
                            <outline text="Recent technological advances in making communication more affordable and computation faster, and the change in norms regarding the use of technology have enabled a range of new applications and systems that collect data from humans." complete="true"/>
                            <outline text="The concept of Human-as-a-Sensor (HaaS) as introduced in \cite{} formalises a methodology where humans are the primary source of information instead of automated sensors. " complete="true"/>
                            <outline text="This paradigm is employed in typical examples such as  " _note="[https://dynalist.io/d/FHihBSUCfC2K3Ytn6mdZ0vkB#z=Twa0Q-RC6u1_3piRvfePoj5O](https://dynalist.io/d/FHihBSUCfC2K3Ytn6mdZ0vkB#z=Twa0Q-RC6u1_3piRvfePoj5O)"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="MOTIVATION">
                            <outline text="However, this approach is not without cyber security challenges."/>
                            <outline text="Humans can sometimes give false reports, either unintentionally or maliciously, and reports could also be communicated over an insecure channel leading to delay, interruption, spoofing or modification. This is a major problem for law enforcement and civil protection agencies that are recipients of HaaS reports. "/>
                            <outline text="Thus, as already reported in [], the main challenge lies in developing a model that might assess the credibility of resulting reports by predict possible ways in which cybercriminals can manipulate HaaS, or how humans might be socially engineered to provide unreliable information."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="CONTRIBUTION">
                            <outline text="In our model, we propose a game theorethical model to assess the reliability of HaaS reports between a reports receiver that could be a government agency and  users that detect and report events or incidents. "/>
                            <outline text="The objective is to assess the thrustworthiness of the information and consider whether to carry out further actions regarding the overall reliability of a HaaS report."/>
                            <outline text="The report receiver attempts to detect intrusion from an attacker that performs semantic social engineering attacks (location spoofing attacks, spear-phishing, obfuscated URLs, drive-by downloads, spoofed websites, scareware...) that target the user-computer interface in order to deceive a user into performing an action that will breach a system’s information security. "/>
                            <outline text="Since we don't know that the user has given false report due to his lack of knwoledge(without their willingness) or that he has been attacked (bypassed by an attacker), we may look at this as bayesian game between the report receiver and the user that is the source of information. "/>
                            <outline text="Our aim is to avoid the false reports and prevent malicious users from having chances to enforce their misbehaviors."/>
                            <outline text="After analyzing the payoff of both players in each step, a Bayesian Nash Equilibrium will be discussed to help report receiver to make decisions in the games and  triage the review of reports by prioritising the ones that are trusthworthy."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="A Bayesian Static HaaS Game">
                        <outline text="INTRO">
                            <outline text="In this section, we present a two-player static Bayesian game between a HaaS node $$h$$ and a report receiver $$r$$.">
<outline text="In this , both report receiver and users have  some private  information  which  is  not  known  by  another  player."/>
<outline text="The private information affects the game play and is related to   the   player’s   payoff   in   the   game. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Within a HaaS reporting plateform, including a group of human sensor, we categorizes sensor nodes into two categories: Regular and malicious nodes. ">
<outline text="Regular nodes are defined as a set of nodes that will cooperate in the Haas plateform, those nodes can give false reports (can be less accurate) without their willingness. "/>
<outline text="In the other hand, there is malicious nodes that perform attacks and security threats in Haas plateform by disrupting the activities and abuse the users interface.  "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Types" complete="true">
                            <outline text="The notion of type of a player is one of the most important concepts in Bayesian games. Each participant of the  game belongs to a certain  type. Different types of players typically have different payoff functions. "/>
                            <outline text="In the game defined in this paper, the human sensor $$h$$ has the three types  $$M_u$$ (malicious), $$N_u$$ (negligent) and $$T_u$$ (trustworthy) whereas the report receiver $$r$$ has only one, $$N_r$$ (normal). While the human sensor type is private information and the report receiver is uncertain about its opponent's type, the type of the report receiver is public information."/>
                            <outline text="Let $$ \mathcal{T} = \mathcal{T}_h \times \mathcal{T}_h $$ be the type-profile space where $$ \mathcal{T}_r = \{N_r\}$$ and $$ \mathcal{T}_h = \{M_h,N_h,T_h\}$$ are the types for players $$h$$ and $$r$$."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Nature">
                            <outline text="We add a fictious player called \textit{&quot;Nature&quot;} that select the types  of players according to the prior probability distribution. It determines the type of the trustee a trustor encounters. In this settings, Nature decides upon malicious  type and assign him a prior probability $$\pi$$."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Reputation">
                            <outline text="We consider in our game the incentive Reputation that will be denoted by $$R$$. If the user node provide a non-misleading report,its reputation is increased otherwise it's  decreased. The same for the report receiver; If he trust a non-trustworthy report his reputation would decrease and vice-versa. The reputation incentive is the same for report receiver and users."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Strategies">
                            <outline text="The report receiver $$r$$ has two pure strategies: $$s^r \in \{t_r,\overline{t}_r\}$$ . Here $$t_r$$ means to trust the received report, whereas $$\overline{t}_r$$ means no trust, either by recognising the reporting node as malicious or as negligent."/>
                            <outline text="On the other hand, user $$u$$ has two pure strategies : $$S^u = &amp;lt;a_u,c_u&amp;gt;$$. $$a_u$$ means perform an attack by giving misleading reports  and $$c_u$$ means cooperate and try to give the right reports."/>
                            <outline text=" If a malicous node cooperate, it is beacause of deceiving the receiver's reports."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Payoffs analysis">
                            <outline text="\begin{itemize}"/>
                            <outline text="\item$$C_c$$: cost for cooperation when user node $$u$$ chooses to report about an event."/>
                            <outline text="\item$$C_a$$: cost for the attack when maliciuos node chooses to attack(This cost depends on the type of attack but we don't go into details of how to calculate it)."/>
                            <outline text="\item$$G_a$$: Gain that the malicous have after performing an attack that has been trusted by the receiver report."/>
                            <outline text="\item$$C_t$$: cost of trust the receiver pays after trusting a non-trustworthy report(The report receiver takes further investigation after trusting a report which end up to be a misleading one) or non trusting a trustworthy report(the report receiver can take some damage if missing a trustworthy report) ."/>
                            <outline text="\item$$\alpha$$:True positive rate or the rate by which report receiver recognize a malicious node (doesn't Trust a not-trustworthy report)"/>
                            <outline text="\item$$1-\alpha$$:False negative rate or the rate by which report receiver doesn't recognize a malicious report (Trust a not-trustworthy report)"/>
                            <outline text="\item$$\beta$$:False positive rate or the rate by which report receiver doesn't recognize a normal node (doesn't Trust a trustworthy report)"/>
                            <outline text="\item$$1-\beta$$:true negative rate or the rate by which report receiver recognize a normal report (Trust a trustworthy report)"/>
                            <outline text="\item$$\gamma$$: the level of accuracy for a user. This level represents the rate for giving an accurate report since humans could be either professionals or negligents.For a professional $$\gamma=1$$ since he gives always the right report. For a very negligeant user that gives always a false report without his willingles $$\gamma=0$$. $$0&amp;lt;\gamma&amp;lt;1$$ depending on the level of professionalism of the user."/>
                            <outline text="\end{itemize}"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Payoff matrix of the bayesian game">
                            <outline text="Payoff matrix for malicious type $$M_u$$">
<outline text="\[\bordermatrix{~ &amp;amp; t_r &amp;amp; \overline{t}_r \cr">
    <outline text="a_u &amp;amp; G(1-\alpha) - C_a;(C_t+R)(\alpha-1) &amp;amp; -\alpha R;\alpha R \cr">
        <outline text="c_u &amp;amp; (1-\beta)R-C_c;R(1-\beta) &amp;amp; \beta R -C_c;-\beta(R+C_t) \cr}\]"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="In the matrix, for the combination \{Attack,Trust\}, user $$u$$ would benefit after performing an attack for the number of times he has been trusted by the report receiver that depends on the false negative rate $$1-\alpha$$ and pays the cost of the attack. On the other hand,the reputation of the report receiver would decrease  and pays in addition the cost for having trusted a misleading report for how much it has trusted the false report wich depends on the false negative rate."/>
<outline text="For the combinaison \{Attack,Not Trust\}, the user $$u$$ see his reputation decreasing by the times he has been identified as a malicious node that depend on the true positive rate $$\alpha$$ and report receiver would get a positive reputation."/>
<outline text="For the combinaison \{Cooperate,Trust\} (We remind that a malicious can cooperate as to deceive the report receiver). We suppose that the degree of accuracy $$\gamma=1$$ since a malicious would give always an accurate report for deception. The user $$u$$ and the report receiver $$r$$  would see their reputation increases for the times $$r$$ has trusted the report which that depends on the true negative rate $$1-\beta$$ except that $$u$$ pays in addition a cost for cooperating.Same for the combinaison \{Cooperate,Not trust\},the only difference is that we use the false positive rate and the $$r$$ pays a cost of trust $$C_t$$ for the time he hasn't trusted a trsuthworthy report."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Payoff matrix for normal type $$N_u$$">
<outline text="\[\bordermatrix{~ &amp;amp; t_r &amp;amp; \overline{t}_r \cr">
    <outline text="c_u &amp;amp;(1-\beta) \gamma R - C_c;(1-\beta) \gamma R &amp;amp; \gamma \beta R -C_c;-\gamma \beta(R+C_t) \cr}\]"/>
</outline>
<outline text="For the combinaison \{Cooperate,Trust\}, since the normal user $$N_u$$ is not always right when reporting due to his level of profisionalism, he benefits only when $$r$$ trust him  when he gives an accurate report with a probability of $$(1-\beta) \gamma$$ and the player $$r$$ would see also his reputation increase. Same for the combinaison \{Cooperate,not Trust\}, except that $$r$$ pays for the cost of not trusting a trustyworthy report. The action of cooperation for a malicious user is the same for a normal type with $$\gamma=1$$"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Bayesian Game Nash Equilibrium Analysis">
                        <outline text="We can now apply the nash equilibrium solution concept to this game that has been designed. The bayesian Nash equilibrium will be a \textit{triple} of srategies: one for the normal user, another for the malicious user and one for the report receiver. All players want to achieve an optimal payoff where a small deviation on it is less profitable. So, the malicous user want to attack without being identified by the report receiver. As for the report receiver, he want to trust the trustworthy reports  without losing reputation and paying cost of trust because of a false identification."/>
                        <outline text="\subsection{Pure strategy BNE analysis}">
                            <outline text="The first step,as always is to determine the strategies for each player. The report receiver $$r$$ has only two strategies ($$t_r$$,$$\overline{t_r}$$) because he doesn't know the type of the user he's dealing with. In the other hand, user $$u$$ knows his type and the strategies are ($$a_uc_u$$,$$c_uc_u$$), where $$a_uc_u$$ means (\textit{attack if malicious,cooperate if normal}) and $$c_uc_u$$ means  (\textit{cooperate if malicious,cooperate if normal}). The reason the strategy has to specify actions for both types is roughly analogous for the reason the strategy has to specify a complete plan for action in extensive-form games with complete information: the user's optimal action depends on what report receiver will do, which in turn depends on what user would have done. Here, user know his type which is, say malicious. So why should he bother formulating a strategy (The strategy $$a_uc_u$$) for the (non-existant) case where he is normal ? The answer is that to decide what is optimal, he has to predict what report receiver will do. However, report receiver doesn't know his type, so he will be optimizing on the basis of his expectations about what a malicous player would optimally do and what a normal player would optimally do. In other words, the strategy of the malicous player  really represents report receiver expectations. And this is the reason why strategies are composed of two components, where the first component of each pair tells his what to do if he is the malicioustype, and the second component if he is the normal type. The resulting payoff matrix is shown in the following matrix :">
<outline text="\[\bordermatrix{~ &amp;amp; t_r &amp;amp; \overline{t_r} \cr">
    <outline text="a_uc_u &amp;amp; \pi(G(1-\alpha) - C_a)+ (1-\pi)((1-\beta) \gamma R - C_c)  &amp;amp; -\pi\alpha R+(1-\pi)(\gamma \beta R -C_c) \cr">
        <outline text="&amp;amp; \pi(\alpha-1)(C_t+R)+(1-\pi)(1-\beta) \gamma R &amp;amp; \pi \alpha R - (1-\pi)\gamma \beta(R+C_t) \cr">
            <outline text="c_uc_u &amp;amp; \pi((1-\beta)R-C_c)+(1-\pi)((1-\beta) \gamma R - C_c)&amp;amp; \pi(\beta R -C_c)+(1-\pi)(\gamma \beta R -C_c)\cr">
                <outline text="&amp;amp; \pi R(1-\beta)+(1-\pi)(1-\beta) \gamma R &amp;amp;  -\pi \beta(R+C_t) - (1-\pi)\gamma \beta(R+C_t)            \cr"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="\cr">
            <outline text="} \]"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The expected payoff of the report receiver for trusting if user plays ($$a_uc_u$$) is: \\">
<outline text=".\hspace{3cm} $$ E_{u_r}(t_r,a_uc_u) = \pi(\alpha-1)(C_t+R)+(1-\pi)(1-\beta) \gamma R $$ \\"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="And the expected payoff of the report receiver for not trusting if user plays ($$a_uc_u$$) is: \\">
<outline text=".\hspace{4cm}$$E_{u_r}(\overline{t_r},a_uc_u) = \pi \alpha R - (1-\pi)\gamma \beta(R+C_t)  $$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="If $$ E_{u_r}(t_r,a_uc_u) &amp;gt;  E_{u_r}(\overline{t_r},a_uc_u) $$ , which is equivalent to : $$\pi &amp;lt; \frac{\gamma (R+\beta C_t)}{\gamma(R+\beta C_t)+(1-\alpha)C_t+R} $$ , then report receiver $$r$$ plays $$t_r$$. At this stage, we have a pure BNE since the best response for the user after playing $$t_r$$ is \textit{attack if malicous, cooperate if normal}. \\"/>
                            <outline text="In fact,The expected payoff for the user after playing $$a_uc_u$$ if report receiver plays ($$t_r$$) is: \\">
<outline text=".\hspace{3cm} $$ E_{u_u}(a_uc_u,t_r) = \pi(G(1-\alpha) - C_a)+ (1-\pi)((1-\beta) \gamma R - C_c) $$ \\"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="And the expected payoff for the user after playing $$a_uc_u$$  if report receiver plays ($$t_r$$) is: \\">
<outline text=".\hspace{3cm}$$E_{u_u}(c_uc_u,t_r) = \pi((1-\beta)R-C_c)+(1-\pi)((1-\beta) \gamma R - C_c) $$ \\"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="If  $$ E_{u_u}(a_uc_u,t_r) = E_{u_u}(c_uc_u,t_r) $$, we have : $$G-C_a-\alpha G = R-C_c-\beta R$$. We can see that the term on the left of the equality represents the cost benefit of the gain after performing an attack by the user and the term on the left the cost benefit of the reputation due to cooperation. Assuming that the attacker tend to attack without being identified by the report receiver, we can assume that $$E_{u_u}(a_uc_u,t_r) &amp;gt; E_{u_u}(c_uc_u,t_r)$$. So \{\textbf{Attack if malicious,cooperate if normal,report receiver trust,(Malicious type having a probability less than $$\boldsymbol{\pi}$$)}\} is a pure BNE. \\"/>
                            <outline text="The expected payoff of the report receiver $$r$$ for trusting if the user plays ($$c_uc_u$$) is always bigger than the one for not trusting no matter the value of $$\pi$$, which is logic since the two types of users are from cooperating one, and since we have prouven that the best response for user in case the report receiver trust is to attack for the malicous type,\{\textbf{Cooperate if malicious,cooperate if normal,report receiver trust}\} is not a pure BNE."/>
                            <outline text="If $$ E_{u_r}(t_r) &amp;lt;  E_{u_r}(\overline{t_r}) $$ , which is equivalent to : $$\pi &amp;gt; \frac{\gamma (R+\beta C_t)}{\gamma(R+\beta C_t)+(1-\alpha)C_t+R} $$ , then report receiver $$r$$ plays $$\overline{t_r}$$. At this stage, we have a pure BNE depending on the best reponse of the user.In fact,the expected payoff for the user after playing $$a_uc_u$$ if report receiver plays ($$\overline{t_r}$$) is: \\">
<outline text=".\hspace{3.5cm} $$ E_{u_u}(a_uc_u,\overline{t_r}) = -\pi\alpha R+(1-\pi)(\gamma \beta R -C_c)$$ \\"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="And the expected payoff for the user after playing $$a_uc_u$$  if report receiver plays ($$t_r$$) is: \\">
<outline text=".\hspace{3cm}$$E_{u_u}(c_uc_u,\overline{t_r}) = \pi(\beta R -C_c)+(1-\pi)(\gamma \beta R -C_c) $$ \\"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="If $$ E_{u_u}(a_uc_u,\overline{t_r}) &amp;gt; E_{u_u}(c_uc_u,\overline{t_r})$$ or $$R &amp;lt; \frac{C_c}{\alpha+\beta}$$,with this condition \{\textbf{Attack if malicious,cooperate if normal,report receiver doesn't trust,(Malicious type having a probability bigger than $$\boldsymbol{\pi}$$)}\} is a BNE. That means that report receiver shouldn't increase the reputation of users more than $$\frac{C_c}{\alpha+\beta}$$, otherwise the malicious type will switch his strategy to cooperation to gain more reputation that would deceive the report receiver $$r$$ and there won't be any BNE in this case."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="\subsection{Mixed strategy BNE analysis}">
                            <outline text="Assume the probabilities of playing each action are as shown in the matrices below. $$y$$ is the probability report receiver plays $$t_r$$ (not conditional on the matrix since this is an information report receiver $$r$$ does not have), $$x$$ is the probability malicious user type plays $$a_u$$. The probability normal type plays $$c_u$$ is $$1$$ since it's the unique strategy for him  ."/>
                            <outline text="\[ \kbordermatrix{\mbox{Malicious}&amp;amp;y&amp;amp;1-y\\"/>
                            <outline text="x &amp;amp; G(1-\alpha) - C_a,(C_t+R)(\alpha-1) &amp;amp; -\alpha R,\alpha R \\"/>
                            <outline text="1-x&amp;amp; (1-\beta)R-C_c,R(1-\beta) &amp;amp; \beta R -C_c,-\beta(R+C_t)"/>
                            <outline text="}\]"/>
                            <outline text="\[\"/>
                            <outline text="\kbordermatrix{\mbox{Normal}&amp;amp;y&amp;amp;1-y\\"/>
                            <outline text="1&amp;amp;(1-\beta) \gamma R - C_c,(1-\beta) \gamma R &amp;amp; \gamma \beta R -C_c,-\gamma \beta(R+C_t)\\"/>
                            <outline text="}\]"/>
                            <outline text="There is still one condition to be taken also into account,when :$$\pi = \frac{\gamma (R+\beta C_t)}{\gamma(R+\beta C_t)+(1-\alpha)C_t+R} $$. It means that from report receiver $$r$$ standpoint there is no difference between the action of trusting or not trusting. This principe of indifference for choosing an action profile doesn't make any difference in the payoff of report receiver (He just flips a coin and whatever the action is, it doesn't matter). This what we call \textsc{&quot;Mixing&quot;}. It means that $$r$$ is mixing his strategies. \\"/>
                            <outline text="To find mixed Bayesian Nash Equilibrium strategy for the user of malicious type, we should put equal the expected payoff from trusting and not trusting of the report receiver $$r$$."/>
                            <outline text="The expected payoff of report receiver from trusting is : \\"/>
                            <outline text=".\hspace{3cm} $$ E_{u_r}(t_r) = \pi[x(C_t+R)(\alpha-1)+(1-x)(1-\beta)R]+(1-\pi)(1-\beta)\gamma R$$\\"/>
                            <outline text="And the expected payoff of report receiver from not trusting is : \\"/>
                            <outline text=".\hspace{3.5cm} $$ E_{u_r}(\overline{t_r}) = \pi[x\alpha R-(1-x)\beta(R+C_t)]-(1-\pi)\gamma \beta (R+C_t)$$ \\"/>
                            <outline text="Thus, with $$ E_{u_r}(t_r) =   E_{u_r}(\overline{t_r})$$, we reach : $$ x^\star = \frac{(R+\beta C_t)(-\gamma -\pi(1-\gamma))}{\pi(\alpha -\beta -1)} $$. In this condition, the attacker is mixing his pure strategies, the user of malicious type should attack with the optimal probability $$x^\star$$ and reach the equilibrium strategy."/>
                            <outline text="On the other hand, the report recevier $$r$$ is also mixing his pure strategies, so with that probability the report receiver $$r$$ should trust when the user $$u$$ is indifferent between choosing attack or cooperating. As to find this time the mixed Bayesian Nash Equilibrium strategy for the report receiver, we should put equal the expected payoff from attacking and cooperating of the user of malicous type.\\"/>
                            <outline text=".\hspace{3cm} $$ E_{u_u}(a_u) = y[G(1-\alpha) - C_a]+(1-y)(-\alpha R)$$\\"/>
                            <outline text="And the expected payoff of report receiver from not trusting is : \\"/>
                            <outline text=".\hspace{3.5cm} $$ E_{u_u}(c_u) = y[(1-\beta)R-C_c]+(1-y)[\beta R -C_c]$$ \\"/>
                            <outline text="Thus, with $$ E_{u_u}(a_u) =   E_{u_u}(\overline{c_u})$$, we reach : $$ y^\star = \frac{(\alpha +\beta)R-C_c}{(G-R)(1-\alpha)+2C_c-C_a} $$. In this condition, the report receiver has done a mixing on his pure strategies, $$r$$ should trust with the optimal probability $$y^\star$$ and reach the equilibrium strategy. \\"/>
                            <outline text="After finding $$y^\star$$ and $$x^\star$$, we can say that user $$u$$type can perform an attack with the probability of $$x^\star$$ if he is a maliciuos type and cooperate otherwise, and the report receiver $$r$$ will trust with the optimal probability of $$y^\star$$. Therfore, \{\textbf{Attack if malicious with probability of $$\boldsymbol{x^\star}$$ ,cooperate if normal,report receiver trust with probability of $$\boldsymbol{y^\star}$$}\} is a mixed BNE."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="References">
                        <outline text="Mohi, M.; Movaghar, A.; Zadeh, P. A Bayesian game approach for preventing DoS attacks in wireless sensor networks. In __Proceedings of 2009 WRI International Conference on Communications and Mobile Computing__, Kunming, China, 6–8 January 2009."/>
                        <outline text="Estiri, M. and Khademzadeh, A., 2010, September. A theoretical signaling game model for intrusion detection in wireless sensor networks. In __Telecommunications Network Strategy and Planning Symposium (NETWORKS), 2010 14th International__ (pp. 1-6). IEEE."/>
