                        <outline text="Heartfield, R., Loukas, G. and Gan, D., 2016. You are probably not the weakest link: Towards practical prediction of susceptibility to semantic social engineering attacks. __IEEE Access, 4__, pp.6910-6928."/>
                        <outline text="Nurse, J.R., Agrafiotis, I., Goldsmith, M., Creese, S. and Lamberts, K., 2014. Two sides of the coin: measuring and communicating the trustworthiness of online information. __Journal of Trust Management, 1__(1), p.5."/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Modelling Security Scenarios Using Game Theory: Breaking Through the Order Two Barrier">
                <outline text="Abstract [Modelling Security Scenarios Using Game Theory: Breaking Through the Order Two Barrier]">
                    <outline text="This paper is concerned with non-cooperative game theory and its application to security, using bimatrix (non zero-sum) complete information games. "/>
                    <outline text="Game theory can help when modelling security scenarios involving attackers and defenders and predicting the likelihood of attack. "/>
                    <outline text="It is shown how to adapt and extend an algebraic generalised eigensystem approach for finding equilibrium solutions of an economical Von Neumann model to a bimatrix game setting. "/>
                    <outline text="This yields an elegant framework to tackle complex bimatrix game models, with a focus on completely mixed solutions. "/>
                    <outline text="Based on these results, a range of existing game models are considered and analysed using "/>
                    <outline text="A generic order three security game is then defined and analysed with respect to the existence of completely mixed solutions. "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="CONTRIBUTIONS">
                    <outline text=", refining results given by . Sufficient algebraic conditions for the existence of an equilibrium strategy of a bimatrix game are derived. It is then established that for games with completely mixed solutions, the sufficient conditions can be strengthened to also become necessary. Finally, #signpost"/>
                    <outline text="The first contribution is purely game-theoretic. Results by Ramaghan, extending early work by Kaplanski on matrix games, are revisited and a remaining gap in his extension to bimatrix games is closed to fully accommodate the structure of the adjoints of the game matrices. Influenced by Thomson and Weil, a linear algebra framework using generalised eigensystems is adopted and it is shown that this yields a natural setting for a subclass of bimatrix games: those with completely mixed solutions. Necessary and sufficient conditions for detecting this subclass are established, based on the regularity of the associated generalised eigensystems and some additional conditions on the corresponding generalised eigenvalues and eigenvectors. "/>
                    <outline text="Our main goal is to provide a general framework"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Introduction #h">
                    <outline text="GT &amp; SECURITY #wfe-ignore-item "/>
                    <outline text="ANALYSING SECURITY SCENARIOS #wfe-ignore-item ">
                        <outline text="Analysing Security Scenarios using GT">
                            <outline text="In this paper we are interested in linking algebraic properties of two independent game matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$ and optimal solutions of the game. "/>
                            <outline text="Our motivation is the use of such a relationship for explicitly solving security games. "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="BARRIER #wfe-ignore-item "/>
                    <outline text="DIRECT SOLVING #wfe-ignore-item ">
                        <outline text="Using game theory to analytically model security scenarios requires the capability to analyse games by studying properties of the involved game matrices, typically based on linear algebra. "/>
                        <outline text="For matrix games, the origins of this approach have been shaped by authors su j Shapley, Karlin and later Thpson and .."/>
                        <outline text="Rather than converting the game into a mathematical program which can be solved using the Simplex algorithm or related approaches, the aim is to give conditions under which it is possible to read game characteristics such as the value and equilibrium solutions from the coefficients of the game matrix. "/>
                        <outline text="an 'active' submatrix of the game matrix "/>
                        <outline text="Exponential algorithm, enumerating all submatrices"/>
                        <outline text="Relevance of Complete Solutions for Security Games">
                            <outline text="Of course the danger of reducing the exercise to a mere security theatre exists but  this is intrinsic flaw of "/>
                            <outline text="It can be argued that the concept of complete solutions and in particular completely mixed ones has "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="CONTRIBUTIONS #wfe-ignore-item ">
                        <outline text="The contributions of this paper are twofold. "/>
                        <outline text="FIRST">
                            <outline text="The first contribution is purely game-theoretic. Results by Ramaghan, extending early work by Kaplanski on matrix games, are revisited and a remaining gap in his extension to bimatrix games is closed to fully accommodate the structure of the adjoints of the game matrices. Influenced by Thomson and Weil, a linear algebra framework using generalised eigensystems is adopted and it is shown that this yields a natural setting for a subclass of bimatrix games: those with completely mixed solutions. Necessary and sufficient conditions for detecting this subclass are established, based on the regularity of the associated generalised eigensystems and some additional conditions on the corresponding generalised eigenvalues and eigenvectors. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="SECOND">
                            <outline text="Based on these results, a second contribution is made for security games. "/>
                            <outline text="A range of existing game models are considered and analysed using "/>
                            <outline text="A generic order three security game is then defined and analysed with respect to the existence of completely mixed solutions. "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="ORGANISATION #wfe-ignore-item ">
                        <outline text="This paper is organised as follows. In Section 2, the game theoretical contribution is developed. In the following section, this is applied to  existing security games while Section 4 uses it to analyse the novel security game. Section 5 is the conclusion. "/>
                    </outline>
