                <outline text="Application to Order Three Security Game #h ">
                    <outline text="Motivation #slide ">
                        <outline text="Most simple scenario"/>
                        <outline text="We only consider one target"/>
                        <outline text="Assume complete protection by defense"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Notations #slide ">
                        <outline text="$$t$$ -- target (an asset $$a$$) "/>
                        <outline text="$$c^{\mathcal{D}}$$ -- the defense cost"/>
                        <outline text="$$l^{\mathcal{D}}$$ -- the defender's loss from an attack"/>
                        <outline text="$$c^{\mathcal{A}}$$ -- the attacker's cost"/>
                        <outline text="$$l^{\mathcal{D}}$$ -- the benefit of the attacker."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Assumptions #slide">
                        <outline text="Principle of Adequate Protection : $$c^{\mathcal{D}} &lt;l^{\mathcal{D}}$$"/>
                        <outline text="Principle of Easiest Attack : $$c^{\mathcal{A}} &lt; l^{\mathcal{D}}$$"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Strategies #slide ">
                        <outline text="$$S_\mathcal{D} = \{defend, not\ defend\} = \{s_d, s_{-d}\}$$ "/>
                        <outline text="$$S_\mathcal{A} = \{attack, not\ attack\} = \{s_a, s_{-a}\}$$ "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Utility Matrix #slide #utility ">
                        <outline text="$$\begin{array}{ | c | c | c| } \hline \mathcal{D} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow &amp; s_a &amp; s_{-{a}} \\ \hline s_d &amp;  - c^{\mathcal{D}}, - c^{\mathcal{A}}&amp;  -c^{\mathcal{D}},  0 \\ \hline s_{-{d}} &amp;  -l^{\mathcal{D}},  l^{\mathcal{D}}- c^{\mathcal{A}} &amp;  0,  0 \\ \hline\end{array}$$"/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Game Analysis #slide">
                        <outline text="There is a unique mixed NE solution ">
                            <outline text="$$x^{*} = \frac{l^{\mathcal{D}}-c^{\mathcal{A}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}} = 1 - \frac{c^{\mathcal{A}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}}$$"/>
                            <outline text="$$y^{*} = \frac{c^{\mathcal{D}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}}$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The corresponding optimal expected utilities are:">
                            <outline text=" $$s^{*}_d = -c^{\mathcal{D}} $$"/>
                            <outline text="$$s^{*}_a =  0 $$ "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The game is strategically zero-sum [1]"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Discussion #slide ">
                        <outline text="Is it worth it for the defender to play the game if : $$c^{\mathcal{D}} =l^{\mathcal{D}}$$ ?"/>
                        <outline text="s it worth it for the attacker to play the game if : $$c^{\mathcal{A}} =l^{\mathcal{D}}$$ ?"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="References #slide">
                        <outline text="[1] - __Strategically zero-sum games: The class of games whose completely mixed equilibria cannot be improved upon__ - International Journal of Game Theory, 1978, Volume 7, Number 3-4, Page 201 - H. Moulin, J. -P. Vial"/>
                        <outline text="[2] - Maghrabi, L., Pfluegel, E., Al-Fagih, L., Graf, R., Settanni, G., &amp; Skopik, F. (2017). Improved software vulnerability patching techniques using CVSS and game theory. In 2017 International Conference on Cyber Security And Protection Of Digital Services, Cyber Security 2017. Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers Inc. https://doi.org/10.1109/CyberSecPODS.2017.8074856"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Narrative">
                        <outline text="We denote by $$S_{\mathcal{D}}=\{d,\overline{d}\}$$ the strategy set of the Defender, where $$d$$ corresponds to the strategy that the Defender patches $$v$$ and $$\overline{d}$$ corresponds to the strategy that the Defender does not patch $$v$$. Likewise, the strategy set of the Attacker is given by $$S_{\mathcal{A}}=\{a,\overline{a}\}$$, where $$a$$ corresponds to the strategy of the Attacker to exploit $$v$$ and $$\overline{a}$$ that the Attacker does not attempt to exploit $$v$$) respectively, e.g. by running some malware. "/>
                        <outline text="To patch the vulnerability, we assume that there is an associate cost, $$c^{\mathcal{D}}$$ for the Defender. To exploit vulnerability $$v$$, we assume that there is a cost $$c^{\mathcal{A}}$$ for the Attacker and a benefit $$b^{\mathcal{A}}$$. We assume that this benefit matches a loss $$l^{\mathcal{D}} = b^{\mathcal{A}}$$ for the Attacker. % #gamesec"/>
                        <outline text="This game has been studied in the past (see e.g. \cite{@Samarji2015}) and is suitable for our scenario which is based on a single asset vulnerability assessment. It is not the specialisation of a big security game. "/>
                        <outline text="Focusing on the single software asset that contains a vulnerability, we define a \emph{single-target small security game}  in normal form through the following payoff matrix $$\begin{array}{ | c | c | c | } \hline {\mathcal{D}} \downarrow {\mathcal{A}} \rightarrow &amp; a &amp; \overline{a} \\ \hline d &amp;  - c^{\mathcal{D}}, - c^{\mathcal{A}} &amp;  -c^{\mathcal{D}},  0 \\ \hline \overline{d} &amp;  -l^{\mathcal{D}},  l^{\mathcal{D}}- c^{\mathcal{A}} &amp;  0,  0 \\ \hline \end{array}$$where the rows correspond to the pure strategies available to the defender $${\mathcal{D}}$$ and the columns are the attacker's $${\mathcal{A}}$$ pure strategies. Here  we assume that the attacker's benefit equals the loss of the defender."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Refined AD Game">
                        <outline text="$$\begin{array}{ c | c | c | c}  {\mathcal{D}} \downarrow {\mathcal{A}} \rightarrow &amp; aa &amp; a &amp; -{a} \\ \hline dd &amp;  - c_{dd}, - c_{aa} &amp; -c_{dd}, -\tilde{c}_a&amp;  -c_{dd},  0 \\ \hline d &amp; -\tilde{l}_{aa} -c_d,\tilde{b}_{aa}  - \tilde{c}_{aa} &amp; -c_d,  -c_a &amp;  -c_d,  0 \\ \hline -{d} &amp; -l_{aa}  , -b_{aa}  - c_{aa} &amp; -l_a, - b_a- c_a &amp;  0,  0  \end{array}$$"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="A Matrix-based Space-Efficient Online Secret Sharing Scheme" _note="https://www.overleaf.com/project/58286fcac9ed824a3d0d13a1 #h &#xA;https://workflowy.com/#/a3887849d25b&#xA;">
                <outline text="Eckhard Pfluegel, Nigel Atkins, Mark Jones #authors"/>
                <outline text="Abstract">
                    <outline text="This paper explores the use of of matrix canonical normal forms for designing space-efficient online secret sharing schemes. "/>
                    <outline text="We review and improve two deterministic schemes that have been suggested in the literature, based on the rational Jordan normal form of a square matrix. "/>
                    <outline text=""/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Introduction #h">
                    <outline text="Secret sharing is a popular cryptographic techniques, which is enjoying increased popularity in important application area as. Frequently, sharing of large amounts of data is required and specialist space-efficient secret sharing schemes have been presented in the literature. The increase in efficiency leads to less security, and space-efficient schemes need to offer computational security.">
                        <outline text="The early method published by Shamir #cite:shamir1979share was based on polynomial interpolation. "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="The standard approach has been presented by[], however this technique needs strong encryption such as the industrial-strength AES algorithm. This results in a computational security, where the length of the key controls the security of the scheme.">
                        <outline text="Krawczyk #cite:krawczyk1994secret introduced a method with short shares, using a weaker notion of security. "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="An interesting question is whether we can find alternative schemes, replacing the need for strong encryption. One idea is to shift some of the complexity inherent in the secret data into the scheme, alleviating the need for complex encryption."/>
                    <outline text="A popular class of space-efficient schemes is based on polynomials, thereby generalising Simeone secret scheme to convert a given secret into a polynomial. This leads to the class of Ramp secret sharing schemes, popular in applications such as cloud security []. "/>
                    <outline text="Related schemes use a different distribution of the secret data into coefficients of the polynomial, however the resulting security is weaker."/>
                    <outline text="In this paper, we are interested in exploiting linear algebra properties of matrices in order to implement space-efficient online secret sharing schemes.">
                        <outline text="The method introduced by Bai #cite:bai2006strong converts a scalar secret to a matrix and exploits linear algebra to further reduce share sizes. In the paper by Yang and Liu #cite:yang2009short, the use of the canonical Jordan normal form significantly shortens shares. "/>
                        <outline text="Zhao et. al. #cite:zhao2012secret present a sophisticated scheme which is also extended to provide a verifiable secret sharing scheme."/>
                        <outline text="#cite:pfluegel2013probabilistic ">
                            <outline text="\item Inspired by previous matrix-based work, but avoid Jordan normal form"/>
                            <outline text="\item Propose a probabilistic algorithm, based on using companion form"/>
                            <outline text="\item We achieve similarly short shares as Yang and Zhao, but are more efficient">
<outline text="\end{itemize}"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="\item This yields a probabilistic online secret sharing scheme with small expected share size"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="%       \item Aspects to consider: security, cost  and space requirements"/>
                    <outline text="\subsection{Our Approach}"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Previous Work #h">
                    <outline text="SIGNPOST #wfe-ignore-item ">
                        <outline text="In this section, we review matrix-based methods for designing space-efficient online secret sharing schemes, that have been published in the literature. We compare and contrast the space efficiency, computational complexity and security of these schemes and point out some existing weaknesses. "/>
                        <outline text="Secret Sharing is a key-less technique for protecting information as an alternative to encryption. It is based on the idea that given a secret $$s$$, a dealer will divide it into $$n$$ shares amongst players. A $$(k,n)$$-threshold perfect secret sharing scheme has the following properties:">
                            <outline text="The secret $$s$$ can be divided into $$n$$ shares. #item "/>
                            <outline text="Less than $$k$$ users do not gain any information on $$s$$. #item "/>
                            <outline text="If at least $$k$$ players combine their shares, they can reconstruct $$s$$. #item "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="The First Method #h">
                        <outline text="INTRO/SUMMARY #wfe-ignore-item ">
                            <outline text="This method is presented in #cite:yang2009short."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="DESCRIPTION #wfe-ignore-item ">
                            <outline text="In order to implement an online $$(k,n)$$ threshold scheme, the secret $$s$$ is divided into $$k^2$$ chunks of same size which are placed into a matrix $$A$$ according to some scheme. A similarity transformation $$P$$ is computed, such that $$J=P^{-1}AP$$ is in Jordan normal form. The matrix key $$P$$ is then encrypted, using a transposition cipher $$E$$ with a secret key. Here, the key is a sequence of $$k$$ integers corresponding to a permutation $$\pi$$ of columns of $$P$$. The public data are then the list [$$E_K(P),J$$] and the secret information is $$\pi$$. The threshold scheme is designed by using $$k$$ instances of an ideal secret sharing scheme such as Shamir’s scheme #cite:shamir1979share to share $$\pi$$ with $$n$$ users."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="ANALYSIS">
                            <outline text="CORRECTNESS">
<outline text="In order to reconstruct the secret, a coalition of $$k$$ players combine their shares in order to recover $$K$$. From this, they can decrypt to obtain $$P$$, compute $$A=PJP^{-1}$$, and retrieve $$s$$. This shows the correctness of the scheme."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="ADVANTAGE #wfe-ignore-item ">
<outline text="The main advantage of this method is the small size of the shares. Each player will receive a share of $$E$$, using Shamir secret sharing, of the size $$| E | =k\log k$$ although other schemes could be used. The size of the public data is $$| T | + | J | = | s | + \sqrt{|s|}$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CRITICISM #wfe-ignore-item ">
<outline text="COMPLEXITY #wfe-ignore-item ">
    <outline text="Arithmetic operations will be done in the field $$F_q$$ where $$q\ge |s|/k^2$$ although the field is not specified in #cite:yang2009short."/>
    <outline text="Let us remark that the Jordan normal form is not defined for this field as it might not be algebraically closed. We will hence discuss an adaptated version of #cite:yang2009short where we use the rational Jordan normal form instead. The computational complexity of computing the rational Jordan normal form is $$O(k^4)$$ which is also the overall cost for creating the shares. The cost for reconstructing the secret requires polynomial interpolation and $$O(k^3)$$ field operations for implementing the similarity transformation."/>
</outline>
<outline text="SECURITY #wfe-ignore-item ">
    <outline text="The authors of the paper prove that knowing $$E_K(T)$$ and $$J$$ gives as much information about the secret matrix $$A$$ as can be encoded in the transformation $$T$$. "/>
    <outline text="This similarity transformation could be viewed as a generalised Hill-cipher #cite:trappe2006introduction defined for matrices, consisting of a modular matrix left- and right-multiplication, using $$T$$ as the key."/>
    <outline text="Using information theory, this can be expressed as">
        <outline text="$$H(A|E_K(T),J)=H(T)$$. #eyo-style:Displaymath"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="In order to provide optimal security, weak (low entropy) keys must be avoided. Usually, this is achieved by asserting that keys are uniformly distributed random numbers. It is clear that the secret part (the key $$K$$) is uniformly distributed random data, although the size of the key must be suficiently large and hence for small threshold values $$k$$ this method would not be secure. "/>
    <outline text="However, a more careful analysis shows that this is not the case with the public part. In the discussed method, the matrix key $$T$$ is generated by the algorithm computing the Jordan normal form itself, and as simple counterexamples show\footnote{For example}, the set of similarity transformations will not be uniformly distributed over the set of all $$r$$ by $$r$$ matrices. "/>
    <outline text="Also, the problem of determining the conjugation classes with respect to similarity transformations, of matrices over a finite field, seems difficult #cite:fulman2002random and hence the precise distribution of $$J$$ is unknown."/>
    <outline text="It is claimed that the scheme offers computational security, although no formal proof is given. Computational security then means that no polynomial-time algorithm is able to.."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="The Second Method #h"/>
                    <outline text="The Third Method #h"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Matrix-based Space-Efficient Online Secret Sharing #h "/>
                <outline text="A Probabilistic Method #h">
                    <outline text="Description of Method #h   ">
                        <outline text="Let us review some linear algebra concepts that will be used in the sequel."/>
                        <outline text="Let $$A \in {F}_p^{t \times t}$$. The matrix $$A$$ is __cyclic__ iff it is similar to matrix in __ companion form__ ">
                            <outline text="$$C =\left(\begin{array}{ccccc} 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; \ldots &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \ddots &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \ldots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\ c_{0} &amp; c_{1} &amp; \ldots &amp; c_{t-2} &amp; c_{t-1} \\ \end{array}\right)$$."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Here, we have that $$f (\lambda) = \lambda^{t} - c_{t-1} \lambda^{t-1} - \cdots- c_{1} \lambda - c_{0}$$ is the characteristic polynomial of $$C$$. "/>
                        <outline text="For a cyclic matrix, we have that $$f(\lambda) = \det(C- \lambda I) = \det(A- \lambda I) = m(\lambda)$$ where $$m(\lambda)$$ is the minimal polynomial of $$A$$."/>
                        <outline text="If $$A$$ is cyclic, we can use standard linear algebra techniques  to compute $$C$$"/>
                        <outline text="Algorithm Cyclic_Vector($$A$$)">
                            <outline text="(1) $$v_0:=$$ random vector"/>
                            <outline text="(2) **for** $$i=1$$ **to** $$t-1$$: compute $$v_i:=v_{i-1}A$$"/>
                            <outline text="(3) **if** $$v_0, \ldots, v_{t-1}$$ are linearly independent **then return** $$v_0$$** **else return __FAIL__"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Question: given a secret $$s$$, and a randomly chosen prime number $$p$$, we can convert $$s$$ to a matrix. How likely is this to induce a random cyclic matrix?"/>
                        <outline text="#theorem:[Neumann et al., 1994]">
                            <outline text="If a matrix $$A$$ and a vector $$v$$ are chosen at random, then the probability that $$A$$ is cyclic and $$v$$ is a cyclic vector for $$A$$ is $$(1-p^{-1})(1-p^{-2})\cdots(1-p^{-t}) $$ ."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Matrix Share Size Reduction Algorithm"/>
                        <outline text="This probabilistic algorithm splits secret $$s$$ into public part $$P$$ and (short) secret part $$Q$$"/>
                        <outline text="We use repeated matrix conversion, with increasing prime numbers"/>
                        <outline text="Algorithm MSSR($$s$$)">
                            <outline text="(1) $$p:=2$$"/>
                            <outline text="(2) /* Conversion of secret */">
<outline text="(a) $$p:=$$ next\_prime$$(p)$$"/>
<outline text="(b) Compute the base-$$p$$ digits of $$s$$"/>
<outline text="(c) Convert secret $$s$$ into a $$t \times t$$ matrix $$S$$ by using these digits (padding with 0 if necessary)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="(3) /* Size reduction step */">
<outline text="(a) Attempt to compute cyclic vector $$v$$"/>
<outline text="(b) If not successful, go to Step (2)"/>
<outline text="(c) Construct similarity transformation $$T$$ such that $$C := T^{-1}S T$$ is a companion matrix"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="(4) Put $$P := T$$ and $$Q := [c_0, c_1, \ldots, c_{t-1}, p]$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Our Online Secret Sharing Scheme">
                            <outline text="We use the MSSR algorithm for an online secret sharing scheme with public and secret data">
<outline text="Share creation:">
    <outline text="Compute $$P$$ and $$Q$$ using MSSR algorithm"/>
    <outline text="Publish $$P$$"/>
    <outline text="Share $$Q$$, using any space efficient secret sharing scheme"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Reconstruction of secret:">
    <outline text="Reconstruct the characteristic polynomial $$f$$ and the value of $$p$$ by acquiring at least $$k$$ shares"/>
    <outline text="Build $$C$$ from the $$t$$ coefficients of $$f$$"/>
    <outline text="Compute $$S$$ from $$C$$, by using the public transformation $$T$$ as $$S = T C T ^{-1}$$"/>
    <outline text="Reconstruct $$s$$ from $$S$$ and $$p$$"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="EXAMPLE">
                            <outline text="\subsection{Example (I)}">
<outline text="\begin{itemize}">
    <outline text="\item Given the secret $$s=123456789123456789$$.">
        <outline text="\item The algorithm did not succeed with the choice $$p=2$$, but converts $$s$$ to the matrix below using $$p=3$$:">
            <outline text="\[">
                <outline text="S =  \left( \begin {array}{cccccc} 0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;2\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1">
                    <outline text="&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;1\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;2\\ \noalign{\medskip}2&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0">
                        <outline text="\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1\\ \noalign{\medskip}2&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2">
                            <outline text="\end {array} \right)."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="\]"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="\end{itemize}"/>
<outline text="%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%"/>
<outline text="\subsection{Example (II)}"/>
<outline text="\begin{itemize}">
    <outline text="\item As public data,  we obtain the transformation">
        <outline text="\[">
            <outline text="T = \left( \begin {array}{cccccc} 1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;0\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1">
                <outline text="&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;2\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;2\\ \noalign{\medskip}1&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0">
                    <outline text="\\ \noalign{\medskip}2&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0\\ \noalign{\medskip}2&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0">
                        <outline text="\end {array} \right)"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="\]"/>
                    <outline text="which can be represented as the decimal number 0223308877354326"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="\item Rows of $$T$$ contain cyclic basis $$\{v, vA, vA^2, \ldots vA^{5}\}$$"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="\end{itemize}"/>
<outline text="%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%"/>
<outline text="\subsection{Example (III)}"/>
<outline text="\begin{itemize}">
    <outline text="\item The matrix $$C = T S T^{-1}$$ mod $$3$$ is in companion form:">
        <outline text="\[">
            <outline text="C  =  \left( \begin {array}{cccccc} 0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0">
                <outline text="&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0">
                    <outline text="\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;1\\ \noalign{\medskip}0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;2&amp;amp;1&amp;amp;0">
                        <outline text="\end {array} \right)"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="\]"/>
                    <outline text="\item It is now sufficient to share the vector secret $$[0,0,2,2,1,0]$$ as well as the value $$p=3$$."/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="\end{itemize}"/>
<outline text="%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Analysis of Algorithm #h">
                        <outline text="Expected Space and Cost #h ">
                            <outline text="In #cite:pfluegel2013probabilistic we have shown that the probability of finding a cyclic vector for a random secret matrix $$S$$, using a small prime number $$p$$, is relatively high. In this section, we refine this analysis and give bounds for the expected number of iterations needed when using a sequence of increasing prime numbers. "/>
                            <outline text="We experimentally show that these bounds are reasonably tight."/>
                            <outline text="#lemma:probability-lemma ">
<outline text="The probability that Algorithm 2 successfully computes a companion matrix for a secret matrix $$S$$ and a given prime $$p$$ can be bounded by ">
    <outline text="$$1-p^{-1}-p^{-2}&lt;\text{Prob[companion}_{p}\text{]} &lt; 1-p^{-1}.$$"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="#proof ">
<outline text="This follows directly by revisiting the proofs of Lemma 4.1 and 4.2 in #cite:pfluegel2013probabilistic, and using the estimate">
    <outline text="$$1-p^{-1}-p^{-2} &lt; (1-p^{-1})(1-p^{-2})\cdots(1-p^{-t}) &lt; 1-p^{-1}$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="which is given in #cite:Neumann:1995:Lemma\s\3.5"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="We define the random variable $$X(l)$$ as the probability that the algorithm finishes after exactly $$l$$ iterations. We have">
<outline text="$$X(l)=\text{Prob[companion$_{p_l}$]} \prod_{i=1}^{l-1}(1-\text{Prob[companion$_{p_i}$]})$$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="and using the previous lemma we find the estimate"/>
                            <outline text="#equation:estimate_for_X">
<outline text="$$(1-p_l^{-1}-p_l^{-2})\cdot\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}{p_i^{-1}}&lt;X(l)&lt;;(1-p_l^{-1})\cdot\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}{(p_{i}+1)}{p_i^{-2}}$$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The desired average number of iterations is the expected value of $$X(l)$$">
<outline text="$$E[X]=\sum_{l=1}^{\infty}l X(l)$$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="where we would like to compute an upper and lower bound for the quantity $$E[X]$$. "/>
                            <outline text="This is accomplished via  the following lemma"/>
                            <outline text="#lemma">
<outline text="Let  $$E_{m}$$  denote the partial sum">
    <outline text="$$E_m=\sum_{l=m}^{\infty}l X(l)$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Then for  $$m&gt;4$$ it holds that">
    <outline text="$$E_{m}^{-}&lt; E_m &lt;E_{m}^{+}$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="where">
    <outline text="$$E_{m}^{-}=\frac{(1-p_m^{-1}-p_m^{-2})m(p_{m}+1)}{p_1 \cdots p_{m}}$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="and">
    <outline text="$$E_{m}^{+}=\frac{1}{(p_{m-1})^{m-1}}\frac{mp_{m-1}+1-m}{(p_{m-1}-1)^2}$$."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="#proof">
<outline text="Let us compute the upper bound first. Using the right hand side of (\ref{estimate_for_X}), we have that"/>
<outline text="\begin{equation}"/>
<outline text="\label{partial_sum}">
    <outline text="E_m &amp;lt; \sum_{l=m}^\infty l(1-p_l^{-1})\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}(p_i+1)p_i^{-2}."/>
</outline>
<outline text="\end{equation}"/>
<outline text="We shall find an estimate for the product in (\ref{partial_sum}). First we have $$p_i+1 &lt; p_{i+1}$$ and hence"/>
<outline text="\begin{equation}"/>
<outline text="\label{truncated-product-estimate}">
    <outline text="\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}(p_i+1)p_i^{-2}&amp;lt;\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}p_{i+1}p_i^{-2}=\frac{p_l}{p_1^{2}p_2 \cdots p_{l-1}}."/>
</outline>
<outline text="\end{equation}"/>
<outline text="To further estimate this product, we shall require a result from number theory known as Bertrand's Postulate #cite:hardy1979introduction:Chapter::s::22. This result, despite its name, is a theorem stating that if $$n&gt;1$$, there is a prime between $$n$$ and $$2n$$. We shall use it in the form $$p_{l} &lt;2p_{l-1}$$ for $$l&gt;1$$. Applying this to the product in  (\ref{truncated-product-estimate}), we find"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="\frac{p_l}{p_1^{2}p_2 \cdots p_{l-1}} &amp;lt; \frac{2p_{l-1}}{p_1^{2}p_2 \cdots p_{l-1}} = \frac{1}{p_1p_2 \cdots p_{l-2}}"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="Finally"/>
<outline text="\[">
    <outline text="E_m &amp;lt; \sum_{l=m}^{\infty}\frac{l(1-p_l^{-1})}{p_1\cdots p_{l-2}} &amp;lt; \sum_{l=m}^{\infty}\frac{l}{p_1\cdots p_{l-2}}&amp;lt;"/>
</outline>
<outline text="\frac{1}{p_1 \cdots p_{m-2}}\sum_{l=m}^{\infty}\frac{l}{(p_{l-1})^{l-m}}&amp;lt;"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="\frac{1}{p_1 \cdots p_{m-2}}\sum_{l=m}^{\infty}\frac{l}{(p_{m-1})^{l-m}}="/>
<outline text="\frac{(p_{m-1})^m}{p_1 \cdots p_{m-2}}\sum_{l=m}^{\infty}\frac{l}{(p_{m-1})^{l}}=\frac{1}{(p_{m-1})^{m-1}}\frac{mp_{m-1}+1-m}{(p_{m-1}-1)^2},"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="where the last sum is an arithmetico-geometric series which is summed in the appendix."/>
<outline text="We now turn to a lower estimate for"/>
<outline text="By we have"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="E_m&amp;gt; \sum_{l=m}^{\infty}{l(1-p_l^{-1}-p_l^{-2})}\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}p_{i}^{-1}&amp;gt;(1-p_m^{-1}-p_m^{-2})\sum_{l=m}^{\infty}l\prod_{i=1}^{l-1}p_{i}^{-1}="/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="(1-p_m^{-1}-p_m^{-2})(\frac{m}{p_1 \cdots p_{m-1}}+"/>
<outline text="\frac{m+1}{p_1 \cdots p_{m}}+\frac{m+2}{p_1 \cdots p_{m+1}}+...)"/>
<outline text="&amp;gt;"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="(1-p_m^{-1}-p_m^{-2})\frac{m}{p_1 \cdots p_{m-1}}(1+"/>
<outline text="\frac{1}{p_m}+\frac{1}{p_{m}p_{m+1}}+...)&amp;gt;"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="\frac{(1-p_m^{-1}-p_m^{-2})m(p_{m}+1)}{p_1 \cdots p_{m}}."/>
<outline text="\]"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="#theorem">
<outline text="The expected number of iterations E[X]  that the algorithm MSSR  use satisfies"/>
<outline text="\["/>
<outline text="1.32&amp;lt; E[x] &amp;lt;2.36"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="#proof">
<outline text="By explicit calculation and using \ref{probability_lemma} we find that"/>
<outline text="\[">
    <outline text="1.3185 &amp;lt;\sum_{l=1}^{5}l X(l)&amp;lt;2.3593."/>
</outline>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="Further, by">
    <outline text="\["/>
</outline>
<outline text="E_{6}^{+}&amp;lt;3.710^{-6}"/>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="and">
    <outline text="\[E_{6}^{-}&amp;gt;2.510^{-3}."/>
</outline>
<outline text="\]"/>
<outline text="The result is immediate."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="We summarize our space and cost analysis with the following"/>
                            <outline text="#theorem">
<outline text="Algorithm #ref: is a probabilistic Monte Carlo algorithm with an exponential worst-case run time, as a function of the size of the input $$s$$. The expected reduced share size is $$\Theta(\sqrt{|s|})$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="#proof">
<outline text="The statement about the worst-case analysis follows from the considerations of the previous section. Lemma \ref{iteration_lemma} shows that the expected number of iterations is small. As a consequence, the size of $$p$$ will be negligible, and the expected size of the private data is then $$|Q| = |f| = \Theta(\sqrt{|s|})$$.}"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
<outline text="Space efficiency: ">
    <outline text="Public data: ">
        <outline text="$$|P|=|s|$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Secret data:">
        <outline text="Expected size: $$|Q|=\Theta(\sqrt{|s|})$$"/>
        <outline text="Worst-case size: same as size of secret"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="\item {Cost}:">
    <outline text="\item Expected cost: new result -- we can prove that the expected number of iterations is $$l_E=3$$"/>
    <outline text="Worst-case cost: exponential in size of secret"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
