                <outline text="Appendix #h ">
                    <outline text="Closed form for arithmetico-geometric series #h ">
                        <outline text="#lemma:arithmetico-geo-lemma">
                            <outline text="For any $$|x|&lt;1$$ we have">
<outline text="$$\sum_{i=m}^\infty ix^i=x^{m}\cdot \frac{m+(1-m)x}{(1-x)^2}$$. #displaymaths "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="#proof">
                            <outline text="Starting with the geometric series">
<outline text="$$\sum_{i=m}^\infty x^i=x^{m}\cdot \frac{1}{(1-x)}$$ #displaymaths "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="and differentiating both sides of this equation formally w.r.t. $$x$$, we obtain">
<outline text="$$\sum_{i=m}^\infty ix^{i-1}=x^{m-1}\cdot \frac{m+(1-m)x}{(1-x)^2}$$ #displaymaths "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="which, after multiplying with $$x$$, yields the result."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="ARCHIVE">
                    <outline text="This method is presented in \cite{yang2009short}. In order to realise an  online $$(k,n)$$ threshold scheme, the secret  $$s$$ is divided into $$k^2$$ chunks of the same size which are then placed into a matrix  $$A$$ according to some scheme. A similarity transformation  $$T$$ is computed, such that  $$J=T^{-1}AT$$ is in Jordan normal form.  This similarity transformation could be viewed as a generalised Hill-cipher \cite{trappe2006introduction} defined for matrices, consisting of a modular matrix left- and right-multiplication, using  $$T$$ as the key. The matrix key $$T$$ is then encrypted itself, using a transposition cipher  $$E_K$$ with key $$K$$. Here, $$K$$ is a sequence of $$k$$ integers correcsponding to a permutation of columns of $$T$$. The public data are then the protected matrix key  $$E_K(T)$$ as well as $$J$$, and the secret part is the key $$K$$. The threshold scheme is designed by using $$k$$ instances of an ideal secret sharing scheme such as Shamir to share $$K$$ between $$n$$ users."/>
                    <outline text="In order to reconstruct the secret, a coalition of  $$k$$ players combine their shares in order to recover  $$K$$. From this, they can deduce  $$T$$ and $$A=TJT^{-1}$$, and finally  $$s$$. This shows the correctness of the scheme."/>
                    <outline text="\subsubsection{Security}"/>
                    <outline text="In order to provide optimal security, weak (low entropy) keys must be avoided. Usually, this is achieved by asserting that keys are uniformly distributed random numbers. It is clear that the secret part (the key  $$K$$) is uniformly distributed random data, although the size of the key must be suficiently large and hence for small threshold values $$k$$ this method would not be secure. However, a more careful analysis shows that this is not the case with the public part. In the discussed method, the matrix key  $$T$$ is generated by the algorithm computing the Jordan normal form itself, and as simple counterexamples show\footnote{For example}, the set of similarity transformations will not be uniformly distributed over the set of all $$r$$ by $$r$$ matrices. Also, the problem of determining the conjugation classes with respect to similarity transformations, of matrices over a finite field, seems difficult \cite{fulman2002random} and hence the precise distribution of $$J$$ is unknown."/>
                    <outline text="The authors of the paper prove that knowing $$E_K(T)$$ and $$J$$ gives as much information about the secret matrix $$A$$ as can be encoded in the transformation $$T$$. Using information theory, this can be expressed as"/>
                    <outline text="\[ H(A|J)=H(T). \]"/>
                    <outline text="It is claimed that the scheme offers computational security, although no formal proof is given. Computational security then means that no polynomial-time algorithm is able to.."/>
                    <outline text="\subsubsection{Space-Efficiency}"/>
                    <outline text="The main advantage of this method is the small size of the shares. Each player will receive a share of $$\sigma$$, using Shamir secret sharing, of the size  $$| \sigma | =k\log k$$ although other schemes could be used. The size of the public data is  $$| T | + | J | = | s | + \sqrt{|s|}$$."/>
                    <outline text="\subsubsection{Computational Complexity}"/>
                    <outline text="Arithmetic operations will be done in the field  $$F_q$$ where $$q\ge |s|/k^2$$ although the field is not specified in \cite{yang2009short}."/>
                    <outline text="Let us remark that the Jordan normal form is not defined for this field as it might not be algebraically closed. We will hence discuss an adaptated version of \cite{yang2009short} where we use the rational Jordan normal form instead. The computational complexity of computing the rational Jordan normal form is $$O(k^4)$$ which is also the overall cost for creating the shares. The cost for reconstructing the secret requires polynomial interpolation and $$O(k^3)$$ field operations for implementing the similarity transformation."/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
