                        <outline text="Game Analysis #h2 ">
                            <outline text="In this section, following the analysis of the security game $$\mathcal{G}$$ showing the existence of several NE strategies, their relevance as an effective security recommendation to the utility company is discussed."/>
                            <outline text="Optimal Pure Nash Equilibrium Strategies #h3 " complete="true">
<outline text="To solve this augmented security game, three cases will be considered. This is based on discussing the second order difference $$\Delta=p_{att^*}-p_{att}$$ between the differences $$p_{att^*}=l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$$ and $$p_{att}=l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$." complete="true"/>
<outline text="Case 1 $$(\Delta&gt;0)$$ #h4 " complete="true">
    <outline text="In this case, the existence of a unique pure NE for the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ can be asserted. The corresponding NE strategy is for the utility company to not monitor, and for the attacker to carry out a weak attack. Due to the uniqueness property these solutions are globally optimal. " complete="true"/>
    <outline text="PROPOSITION 1 #wfe-ignore-item "/>
    <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} &gt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a unique pure Nash Equilibrium strategy profile of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}) $$ and the corresponding payoffs $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$ are globally optimal. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop1"/>
    <outline text="PROOF #wfe-ignore-item "/>
    <outline text="First, it needs to be verified that when choosing the pure strategy profile $$(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}) $$, none of the two players benefit from a unilateral change of pure strategy. #eyo-style:Proof">
        <outline text="Focusing on the utility company, the change of strategy $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ diminishes its payoff since $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} &gt; -c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}-l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$$ due to the assumption of a positive monitoring cost. Considering the attacker, the change $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ is not beneficial because of the main assumption $$\Delta&gt;0$$ of this case. Finally, the change of strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{A}_{-att}$$ reduces the payoff due to Assumption #eyo-latex-ref:A4.   Second, a careful inspection of the payoff functions of the remainder of the game, together with the fact that the assumption of Case 1 implies $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} &gt;- c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ shows that there is no other pure NE equilibrium. This completes the proof. "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Case 2 $$(\Delta&lt;0)$$ #h4 " complete="true">
    <outline text="The result in this case is that a unique pure, weak NE exists only under the additional condition that for the utility company, the losses of a strong attack are the same as the monitoring and defence costs. The optimal strategy in this case is to not monitor, and for the attacker to perform a strong attack." complete="true"/>
    <outline text="\Eckhard{We need to explain that this seems a contradictory advice to the utility company, not uncommon for a non-zero-sum game}"/>
    <outline text="PROPOSITION 2 #wfe-ignore-item " complete="true"/>
    <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ and the additional new assumption $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att} = c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$ are satisfied, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a pure weak Nash Equilibrium strategy profile of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att})$$. The corresponding optimal payoffs are $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att} $$. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop2" complete="true"/>
    <outline text="PROOF #wfe-ignore-item"/>
    <outline text="The proof of this proposition is done very similarly to that of Proposition 1 by comparing the changes in payoff, following a unilateral change of strategy.  Focusing first on $$\mathcal{A}$$'s strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$  and moves to either $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$ or $$s^\mathcal{A}_{-att} $$, in either case the corresponding payoff will decrease due to the assumption of this case, or Assumption #eyo-latex-ref:A4. Focusing on $$\mathcal{D}$$, if the utility company switches its strategy from $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}$$ to  $$s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ its payoff does not change due to the additional assumption. This proves the existence of the weak NE, by definition. Uniqueness can be seen similarly to the previous proposition by inspecting all transitions between payoffs of the game matrix. #eyo-style:Proof" complete="true"/>
    <outline text="Without the additional assumption, the augmented security game, similarly to the IDS game, has the same property of circular paths when performing unilateral changes strategy with increasing payoffs, hence prohibiting the existence of any pure equilibrium." complete="true"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Case 3 $$(\Delta=0)$$ #h4 " complete="true">
    <outline text="In this last case, one derives the inequality $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}&gt;- c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ as in Case 1 and obtains a similar but weaker result, as the pure NE is not strict. A formal proof of the following proposition is omitted as it can be done similarly as that of Proposition 1 since the same payoff deviations are involved."/>
    <outline text="PROPOSITION 3 #wfe-ignore-item "/>
    <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a unique pure non-strict Nash Equilibrium strategy profile of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}) $$ and the corresponding optimal payoffs are $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop3"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The Mixed Strategy Case #h3 ">
<outline text="In this section, it is demonstrated how a mixed NE can be found  if Case 2 arises and the required additional assumption for Proposition 4.2 cannot be met. Rather than solving the game generically, a quantitative example with payoff matrices containing real numbers is given. This example is consistent with the experimental data used in the simulated scenario, described in the previous sections of the paper."/>
<outline text="Nash's theorem states that any non-zero sum game admits a NE. Hence, if as in Case 2, no pure NE exists, mixed strategy solutions can be found."/>
