                <outline text="CONCLUSION #wfe-ignore-item ">
                    <outline text="In this paper, a novel class of false data injection attacks on forecasted demand data was investigated. Based on extensive simulations, the impact on typical system parameters such as household bills and PAR value was analysed. Then, the various defence mechanisms against such attacks were considered. Finally, game theory was used to help the utility company with the decision-making of how to spend their defence budget. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="While the use of game theory models to support decision-making in the area of cyber security, applied to a range of domains such as smart scheduling in energy is a promising line of research, there are also reasons why it might be difficult to be accepted and adopted by practitioners. Essentially, the problem is that it requires a contractual agreement between rational players. The recommendations to the utility company based on Propositions 4.1, 4.2 and 4.3 are based on the rational behaviour of all the people involved, such as the security administrators, team managers, people with financial responsibility and many other stakeholders, including the attacker as an individual. This problem can be exemplified when considering the additional equality assumption $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att} = c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$ needed in Case 2 for the result of Proposition 4.2 and more generally, if one observes that in the IDS game, any of the pure strategies turn into non-strict pure NE strategies, if one of the parameters is assumed to be zero. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="However, how acceptable would this additional assumption be in a real-life scenario to humans, who tend to be irrational? And even if such an assumption was deemed plausible, how likely would they follow the advice of a resulting game theoretical model, with all their decisions and actions being influenced by their feelings and emotions?" complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="While a deeper exploration of such questions is not within the scope of this paper, some interesting points can be made when studying how the personal characteristics of a player in this game might influence behaviour when facing indifference, dictated by payoff equality assumptions such as those presented. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="DISCUSSION #wfe-ignore-item">
                        <outline text="SUITABILITY #wfe-ignore-item ">
                            <outline text="__The attack does not require any cost__. This could be an assumption suitable for an extremely motivated or powerful attacker. The defender would have to be convinced that he is mainly dealing with such an attacker. #item"/>
                            <outline text="__There are no costs required for defending__. A big organisation with a large defense budget might be willing to accept this assumption, when playing as defender. #item "/>
                            <outline text="\Eckhard{These two previous points needs discussing as I am not so sure about them.}."/>
                            <outline text="__The costs for mounting an attack match the resulting benefits__. __The defence costs are the same as incurring losses due to an attack__.  These assumptions might be plausible to both defender and attacker, provided they believe that they have reliable sources of information. #item "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="LIKELIHOOD FOLLOWING THE ADVICE OF THE MODEL #wfe-ignore-item ">
                            <outline text="A human attacker will not undertake an attack without gain. At the least, if no financial gain could be expected, there would be a psychological satisfaction or thrill that the attacker would expect as benefit. "/>
                            <outline text="A system administrator might feel uneasy when not applying security defences, even though  states then the indifference of the outcomes. There would be a worry about uncovered risks, not covered by the game theoretical model, leading to a loss after all."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="From this discussion, the need for more sophisticated game theoretical models arises, taking into account the personal profile of an attacker, or the organisational profile of a defender. One can expect more powerful classes of games such as incomplete information games or stochastic games to be increasingly used respond to this challenge." complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="INBOX  #wfe-ignore-outline ">
                        <outline text="The resulting model extends a previously considered IDS game, and the design of payoff functions specific to the scenario leads to a range of scenarios, WE characterised by certain assumptions, which aid the decision-making process for the utility company."/>
                        <outline text="To model the interaction between a utility company and an attacker, and to give practical advice. "/>
                        <outline text="This translates to an equality assumption in a subset of the augmented game in this paper, and includes the additional assumption discussed in Case 2. "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Final Notes">
                    <outline text="I found a couple of well-known concepts for the mixed strategy. It would be great if we can adopt 2nd and 3rd interpretation to our game. "/>
                    <outline text="">
                        <outline text="1.    Randomization: Randomization, central in mixed strategies, lacks behavioral support. Seldom do people make their choices following a lottery. This behavioral problem is compounded by the cognitive difficulty that people are unable to generate random outcomes without the aid of a random or pseudo-random generator.[2]"/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="In 1991,[3] game theorist Ariel Rubinstein described alternative ways of understanding the concept. The first, due to Harsanyi (1973),[4] is called purification, and supposes that the mixed strategies interpretation merely reflects our lack of knowledge of the players' information and decision-making process. Apparently random choices are then seen as consequences of non-specified, payoff-irrelevant exogeneous factors. However, it is unsatisfying to have results that hang on unspecified factors.[3]"/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="2.    imagine the game players standing for a large population of agents. Each of the agents chooses a pure strategy, and the payoff depends on the fraction of agents choosing each strategy. The mixed strategy hence represents the distribution of pure strategies chosen by each population. However, this does not provide any justification for the case when players are individual agents."/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                        <outline text="3.    Aumann and Brandenburger (1995),[5] re-interpreted Nash equilibrium as an equilibrium in beliefs, rather than actions. For instance, in rock-paper-scissors an equilibrium in beliefs would have each player believing the other was equally likely to play each strategy. This interpretation weakens the predictive power of Nash equilibrium, however, since it is possible in such an equilibrium for each player to actually play a pure strategy of Rock."/>
                        <outline text=""/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text=""/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="DRAFTS">
                    <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att\degree} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att\degree} &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits no pure NE. \label{prop2} #eyo-style:Proposition "/>
                    <outline text="The proof of this proposition is done very similarly to that of Proposition 1 by comparing the changes in payoff, following a unilateral change of strategy.  It is clear that there is no pure NE in the game restricted to the attacker strategies $$s^{\mathcal{A}}_{att}$$ and $$s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}$$, as the resulting subgame is identical to the IDS game. When augmented by the weak attack strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^\degree}$$, two cases may arise, depending on which of the strategy changes  $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att^\degree}$$ or $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^\degree} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$, starting from the initial strategy profile $$(s^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon},s^\mathcal{A}_{att})$$, lead to an increased payoff for the attacker. #eyo-style:Proof ">
                        <outline text="In the first case, one observes the sequence of strategy changes $$s^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} \rightarrow s^{\mathcal{U}}_{-mon}$$, $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^\degree}\rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ and $$s^{\mathcal{U}}_{-mon}\rightarrow s^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon}$$ leading back to the original strategy profile. These changes entail increased payoffs due to the assumption of positive monitoring cost, the condition $$\Delta&lt;0$$ and the Security Game Assumptions. In the second case, the unilateral payoff change joins the circular  path of the IDS game, from which the proof follows as shown earlier."/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
