                        <outline text="The Attacker, for her part, has three different strategies: she can decide to make a detectable attack, to make an undetectable attack or not to attack. "/>
                        <outline text="The security game we are considering beetween the Attacker and the Utility company is a non-zero sum complete information game, that can be represented in normal form as follows:"/>
                        <outline text="$$\begin{array}{ c | c | c | c }  \mathcal{U} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow &amp; s^\mathcal{A}_{udet} &amp; s^\mathcal{A}_{det}  &amp; s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att} \\  s^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} &amp;  -c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} - l^\mathcal{U}_{udet}, l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} - c^\mathcal{A}_{udet} &amp; -c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} -c^\mathcal{U}_{def}, - c^{\mathcal{A}}_{det} &amp; -c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} ,0\\  s^{\mathcal{U}}_{-mon} &amp;  -l^\mathcal{U}_{udet}, l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} - c^\mathcal{A}_{udet}  &amp; -l^{\mathcal{U}}_{det}, l^{\mathcal{U}}_{det}- c^{\mathcal{A}}_{det} &amp; 0,0 \end{array}$$ #displaymaths"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="In  a typical security game, the defender (UC in our case) will try to spend at the most what she looses. Hence, we can assume that the cost of monitoring is less than the losses incurred by an undetectable attack $$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} $$ #ref:here:A1 . Furthermore, the sum of monitoring and defense costs will be less than the loss resulting of an attack $$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def} \le l^\mathcal{U}_{det} $$ #ref:here:A2 . Similarely, the attacker will not spend more than what he expects to gain, we will assume  $$c^\mathcal{A}_{udet}  &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} $$ #ref:here:A3 and $$c^\mathcal{A}_{det}  &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{det} $$ #ref:here:A4 ."/>
                    <outline text="Guided by the experimental results in Section #wfe-latex-ref:vulnerability_section   , we can also assume that the effort for a detectable attack is higher than that for an undetectable attack, and a similar observation applies to the losses. This leads to the additional assumptions $$c^\mathcal{A}_{det} &gt; c^\mathcal{A}_{udet}$$ #ref:here:A5 and $$l^{\mathcal{U}}_{det}&gt;l^{\mathcal{U}}_{udet} $$ #ref:here:A6 ."/>
                    <outline text="Game-Theoretic Defence Strategy #h1 OLD">
                        <outline text="#eyo-latex-label:sec-game-defence"/>
                        <outline text="When planning to defend against the false data injection attacks described in the previous section, the utility company has to decide how to allocate resources for the defence as typically, organisations have restricted budgets. In this section, it is proposed to use game theory in order to support this decision-making process. #signpost  "/>
                        <outline text="The security game will be motivated and introduced based on detailing the payoff functions of the two players describing the game normal form. This will be followed by solving the game using various assumptions. Finally, the solutions will be discussed with respect to their implications for our simulated scenario and also potential alternatives."/>
                        <outline text="% TEMP">
                            <outline text="Game Theory for Security #h2 " complete="true">
<outline text="Game theory is increasingly being employed for modelling attacker-defender scenarios in cyber security, for a broad range of  scenarios such as intrusion detection in network security \cite{Alpcan2010}, managing the security of information in an organisation \cite{Panaousis2014CybersecurityApproach} and predicting the likelihood of cyber attacks \cite{Bao2017HowGames}." complete="true"/>
<outline text="The principal idea of non-cooperative game theory is to consider rational players, choosing between actions that entail payoffs consisting of gains (benefits) and losses (costs), in order to form optimal strategies seeking to maximise their payoffs. A game is solved using the fundamental concept of the Nash Equilibrium. An optimal Nash Equilibrium (NE) strategy has a local maximum property: any single player deviating from the NE strategy will suffer a reduced payoff. It is important to note that only unilateral strategy changes are considered in this concept. Hence applying game theory for real-life scenarios is only a valid and useful tool if all participants agree to adopt it as a contract for strategic decision-making, in the modelled scenario. " complete="true"/>
<outline text="Zero-sum games are used for simple scenarios where it can be assumed that the gains or losses of one player are balanced out by those for the remaining ones. For more complex scenarios, nonzero-sum games may be required. A nonzero-sum game may not have any clear winner or looser, and its NE strategies may not necessarily be unique, implying that different optimal strategies with different payoffs exist. An NE strategy whose payoff is largest amongst all other optimal solutions, is referred to as globally optimal solution." complete="true"/>
<outline text="An arbitrary game need not always have to have optimal solutions following the above definition, and this can be resolved using the more general idea of mixed strategies. Mixed strategies extend pure strategies by introducing probability distributions. Nash's theorem then states that any $$n$$-player non-cooperative game not possessing a pure NE admits a mixed NE. Mixed strategies are very relevant in the context of security games, as most of these games do not have pure NEs. On the other hand, the practical interpretation of mixed NES remains controversial  and for this reason, for the game introduced in this paper, the focus is on pure NEs." complete="true"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Proposed Security Game #h2 ">
<outline text="The proposed security game is a two-player non-zero sum complete information game between the utility company $$\mathcal{U}$$ and the attacker $$\mathcal{A}$$. In a complete information game, parties have full knowledge of the complete set of strategies and corresponding payoffs of all players and the specific selection of actions is based on computing optimal solutions, relying on everyone else proceeding in the same way." complete="true"/>
<outline text="The game is inspired by the Intrusion Detection System (IDS) game of \cite{Alpcan2010} which has been thoroughly analysed in the literature and is well understood. Table \ref{table:game_IDS} illustrates the game where the two strategies available to the defender are to monitor or not, denoted by the strategy space $$S_\mathcal{D} = \{s^\mathcal{D}_{mon},s^\mathcal{D}_{-mon}\}$$, and the attacker chooses between attacking or not attacking: $$S_\mathcal{A} = \{s^\mathcal{A}_{att},s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}\}$$. The positive parameters $$\alpha_c, \alpha_f, \alpha_m, \beta_c$$ and $$\beta_s$$ are used to denote the payoffs corresponding to the various strategies. The main characteristic of this game is the design of the payoff functions in such a way that the monitoring defender only has an incentive to defend in the presence of an attack. The attacker is discouraged from attacking if there is defence in place. This design leads to a circular path when considering payoff-incrementing unilateral changes of strategy, hence prohibiting the existence of a pure Nash Equilibrium." complete="true">
    <outline text="\bgroup \def\arraystretch{1.5} \begin{table}\label{table:game_IDS} \centering \caption{IDS Game of \cite{Alpcan2010} in Normal Form} \begin{tabular}{ c | cc | cc } $\mathcal{D} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow$ &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c} {$s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c}{$s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}$} \\\hline $s^{\mathcal{D}}_{mon}$ &amp; $\alpha_{c}$, &amp;$- \beta_{c}$ &amp; $-\alpha_{f}$, &amp;$0$\\\hline $s^{\mathcal{D}}_{-mon}$ &amp; $-\alpha_{m}$, &amp;$\beta_{s}$ &amp; $0$, &amp;$0$ \end{tabular} \end{table} \egroup "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Description of Game #h3 " complete="true">
    <outline text="In this section, an augmented security game is introduced, extending the IDS game introduced in the previous section by an additional action. The rationale behind this extended game model is twofold: Section \ref{sys_monitor} demonstrated the existence of low-impact attacks which cannot be detected by standard monitoring techniques, and it would be desirable to capture these in a more sophisticated game model. Second, an extended game might better match real-world scenarios and might lead to simpler solutions, in this case pure equilibria rather than mixed ones. " complete="true"/>
    <outline text="STRATEGIES #wfe-ignore-item " complete="true">
        <outline text="Section #wfe-latex-ref:vulnerability_section presented three possible monitoring strategies for $$\mathcal{U}$$: to monitor the daily average of forecasting data, to inspect the daily shape of the aggregated forecast, and to inspect the individual forecast data with the same level of detail. In this paper, the assumption is made that the first and second monitoring strategies are most useful in a realistic setting, as they have an observable impact on the strength and outcome of successful attacks while the third monitoring strategy merely eliminates attacks that are possible for weaker monitoring levels. Furthermore, as the data of aggregated forecasts is readily available to the utility company, the first monitoring strategy is not very costly and will be identified with the strategy $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}$$. The second monitoring strategy will be denoted as $$ s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ so that the strategy space for the defender $$\mathcal{U}$$ is as in the previous game $$S_\mathcal{U} = \{s^\mathcal{U}_{mon},s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}\}$$. The attacker $$\mathcal{A}$$ has three different strategies: to attack strongly with high impact, to perform a weaker attack with low impact, or not to attack at all. This will be denoted by the strategy space $$S_\mathcal{A} = \{s^\mathcal{A}_{att},s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*},s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}\}$$. " complete="true"/>
        <outline text="The additional attack strategy offers an alternative incentive of not monitoring to the utility company, preferring to save monitoring cost when facing a weak attack. No assumption is made on the relationship between the attacker's overall payoff when choosing the two different attack types, and a discussion of conditions clarifying this relationship will be the main subject of the game analysis in the next section." complete="true"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="GAME #wfe-ignore-item " complete="true">
        <outline text="The following notations for the payoffs for $$\mathcal{U}$$ are introduced: $$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ is the cost for monitoring  the daily shape of the aggregated forecast (second monitoring strategy) and $$c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$ is an additonal cost for investing in defense mechanisms such as actions discussed in Section \ref{attack_mitigation}. Losses from weak and strong attacks are denoted by $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att}$$ and $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$$ respecively. The payoff functions corresponding to $$\mathcal{A}$$ are the benefits and costs associated with weak and strong attacks, denoted by $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$, $$c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$$ as well as $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att} $$ and $$c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$. Using these notations, the proposed security game $$\mathcal{G}$$ can be represented in normal form as shown in Table \ref{tab:game_NF}.">
            <outline text=" \bgroup     \def\arraystretch{1.5}     \begin{table*}\label{tab:game_NF}         \centering         \caption{Security Game in Normal Form}         \begin{tabular}{ c | cc | cc | cc }         $\mathcal{U} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow$ &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c}{$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{$s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c}{$s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}$} \\\hline         $s^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon}$ &amp; $-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} - l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$, &amp;$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$ &amp; $-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} -c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$, &amp;$- c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att}$ &amp; $-c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$, &amp;$0$\\\hline         $s^{\mathcal{U}}_{-mon}$ &amp; $-l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$, &amp;$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$ &amp; $-l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att}$, &amp;$l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att}- c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att}$ &amp; $0$, &amp;$0$         \end{tabular}     \end{table*}     \egroup "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="The monitoring activity always leads to monitoring costs for $$\mathcal{U}$$. If there is no monitoring, $$\mathcal{U}$$ incurs losses $$l_{att^*}^{\mathcal{U}}$$ and $$l_{att}^{\mathcal{U}}$$ due to weak and default attacks. Otherwise, despite monitoring, weak attacks cannot be detected, hence there is a resulting loss $$l_{att^*}^{\mathcal{U}}$$. Strong attacks however are detected and mitigated against through some countermeasures, preventing any losses but leading to a defence cost $$c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$. Finally, if there is no attack, then the only arising non-zero payoff function involved is the monitoring cost for $$\mathcal{U}$$. The attacker $$\mathcal{A}$$ obtains a benefit $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$ from a weak attack, but has to invest attack costs $$c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$. Similarly, the cost $$c^\mathcal{A}_{att} $$ arises from a normal attack, however the model assumes the lack of a benefit for $$\mathcal{A}$$ due to the utility company's defence mechanism. Note that an assumption made in this game is that the benefit of the attacker is the loss of the defender, $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}=l_{att^*}^{\mathcal{U}}$$ and $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att}=l_{att}^{\mathcal{U}}$$. "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Basic Game Assumptions #h3">
    <outline text="\Eckhard{Need to derive these assumptions from IDS Game.}"/>
    <outline text="Adapting the notations from []: #wfe-ignore-outline ">
        <outline text="$$\alpha_c = -c^{\mathcal{U}}_{\mathcal{mon}}-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{def} &lt; 0$$">
            <outline text="Gain from detection: necessary cost to prevent"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\alpha_m={{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{att} &gt; 0$$">
            <outline text="lossess if attack occurs and is not mitigated"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\alpha_f=-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} &lt;0$$ ">
            <outline text="ongoing monitoring cost "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\beta_c=c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att} &gt; 0$$ ">
            <outline text="attack effort"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\beta_s={\mathcal{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{att} - c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att}$$ ">
            <outline text="benefit from (undetected) attack - attack effort"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Assumption:">
            <outline text="$$-\alpha_m \leq \alpha_c$$ $$\Longleftrightarrow$$ $$c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} + c^{\mathcal{U}}_{def}\leq {\mathcal{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{strong}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Since, in a typical security game, the defender ($$\mathcal{U}$$ in this paper) does not spend more on defence than what they can loose from an attack~\cite{}, the cost of monitoring is assumed to be at the most as high as the losses incurred due to any attack."/>
    <outline text="In particular, this implies for a weak attack">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} \leq l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$$ #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A1"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="and that the combined monitoring and defence costs amount to at the most the loss resulting from an attack: ">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def} \le l^\mathcal{U}_{att}$$.  #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A2"/>
        <outline text="$$-\alpha_m \leq \alpha_c$$ $$\Longleftrightarrow$$ $$c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} + c^{\mathcal{U}}_{def}\leq {{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{att}$$ #wfe-ignore-item "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="A similar principle applies to the attacker: $$\mathcal{A}$$ will not spend more on an attack than the expected gain from it, leading to the assumptions ">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} \leq b^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$$ #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A3 "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="and">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att} \leq b^\mathcal{A}_{att} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att}$$. #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A4"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Guided by the experimental results presented in Section #wfe-latex-ref:vulnerability_section, it can also be assumed that the cost for launching an attack is higher than that for a weak attack">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att} &gt; c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$$. #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A5"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Similarly, we assume that an attack leads to higher losses for the utility company: ">
        <outline text="$$l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att}&gt;l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att^*}$$. #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A6"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Game Analysis #h2 ">
<outline text="In this section, following the analysis of the security game $$\mathcal{G}$$ showing the existence of several NE strategies, their relevance as an effective security recommendation to the utility company is discussed."/>
<outline text="Optimal Pure Nash Equilibrium Strategies #h3 ">
    <outline text="To solve this augmented security game, three cases will be considered. This is based on discussing the difference $$\Delta=p_{att^*}-p_{att}$$ between the attacker's payoff functions $$p_{att^*}=l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$$ and $$p_{att}=l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$." complete="true"/>
    <outline text="Case 1 ($$\Delta&gt;0$$) #h4 " complete="true">
        <outline text="In this case, the existence of a unique pure NE for the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ can be asserted. The corresponding NE strategy is for the utility company to not monitor, and for the attacker to carry out a weak attack. Due to the uniqueness property these solutions are optimal. " complete="true"/>
        <outline text="PROPOSITION 1 #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} &gt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a unique pure Nash Equilibrium strategy of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}) $$ and the corresponding payoffs $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$ are optimal. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop1"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="PROOF #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text="First, it needs to be verified that when choosing the pure strategy $$(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}) $$, none of the two players benefit from a unilateral change of pure strategy. #eyo-style:Proof">
                <outline text="Focusing on the utility company, the change of strategy $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ diminishes her payoff since $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} &gt; -c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}-l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*}$$ due to the assumption of a positive monitoring cost. Considering the attacker, the change $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ is not beneficial because of the main assumption of Case 1. Finally, the change of strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{A}_{-att}$$ reduces the payoff due to Assumption #eyo-latex-ref:A3.   Second, a careful inspection of the payoff functions of the remainder of the game, together with the fact that the assumption of Case 1 implies $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} &gt;- c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ shows that there is no other pure NE equilibrium. This completes the proof. "/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
            <outline text="The value of the optimal payoffs for the UC are $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att}$$ and $$ l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}  $$ for the Attacker. #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="![Diagram](https://www.dropbox.com/s/cn2dksuwqdr8h1k/prop3_arrow.png?dl=1) #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="strategy of the form $$(x^*,y^*) $$ where $$ x^* = \begin{pmatrix}  0 &amp;1\end{pmatrix}$$, $$y^* = \begin{pmatrix}  1&amp; 0&amp; 0\end{pmatrix}^T$$ and the corresponding optimal payoffs are  #wfe-ignore-item "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Case 2 ($$\Delta&lt;0$$) #h4 ">
        <outline text="The result in this case is the existence of a unique pure, weak NE under the assumption of an additional condition. \JC{What is a weak NE? What are the optimal actions?}" complete="true"/>
        <outline text="PROPOSITION 2 #wfe-ignore-item " complete="true">
            <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ and additionally $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att} = c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$ are satisfied \JC{make clear this is a new assumption}, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a pure weak Nash Equilibrium strategy of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att}) $$ . The corresponding optimal payoffs are $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att} $$. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop2"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="PROOF #wfe-ignore-item">
            <outline text="The proof of this proposition is done very similarly to that of Proposition 1 by comparing the changes in payoff, following a unilateral change of strategy.  Focusing first on $$\mathcal{A}$$'s strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$  and moves to either $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$ or $$s^\mathcal{A}_{-att} $$, in either case the corresponding payoff will decrease due to the assumption of this case, or Assumption #eyo-latex-ref:A4. Focusing on $$\mathcal{D}$$, if the utility company switches her strategy from $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}$$ to  $$s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ her payoff does not change due to the additional assumption. This proves the existence of the weak NE, by definition. Uniqueness can be seen similarly to the previous proposition by inspecting all transitions between payoffs of the game matrix. #eyo-style:Proof" complete="true"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Without the additional assumption, any such change will follow circular paths, hence prohibiting the existence of any pure equilibrium."/>
        <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
            <outline text="![Diagram](https://www.dropbox.com/s/ayuij6h18qsxphz/prop1_arrow.png?dl=1) #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="https://www.draw.io/?state=%7B%22ids%22:%5B%2210U2gnjq-7fWqTlX1H4mf80KUuayRTAns%22%5D,%22action%22:%22open%22,%22userId%22:%22{userId}%22%7D#G10U2gnjq-7fWqTlX1H4mf80KUuayRTAns"/>
            <outline text="We need to verify that none of the two players benefit from unilateral change of pure strategy, when choosing the NE strategy $$(x^*,y^*)$$. "/>
            <outline text="The first result is the existence of a pure, optimal strategy for the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ indicating that the utility company should not monitor and the attacker should do a attectable attack. If both players choose these strategies, their corresponding payoffs will be $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att}$$  for the utility company and $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att} $$ for the attacker. "/>
            <outline text="To get this result, we need to add three assumptions that doesn't intefer with the ones we already have. And then, the benefit for a attectable attack is exactly the cost of monitoring and defense $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att} = c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$. "/>
            <outline text="However, this would entail a serie of additionnal unilateral strategy changes $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}$$ , $$ s^\mathcal{U}_{mon} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon} $$ and finally   $$ s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Case 3 ($$\Delta=0$$) #h4 " complete="true">
        <outline text="In this last case, one derives the inequality $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}&gt;- c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$ as in Case 1 and obtains a similar but weaker result, as the pure NE is not strict. The proof of the following proposition is omitted and left to the reader."/>
        <outline text="PROPOSITION 3 #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a unique pure non-strict Nash Equilibrium strategy of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att^*}) $$ and the corresponding optimal payoffs are $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att^*} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att^*} $$. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop3"/>
