                            <outline text="Discussion #h2">
<outline text="A simple observation is that in the IDS game, if any of the parameters are additionally assumed to be zero, non-strict pure NE will be obtained. This translates to an equality assumption in Assumptions of the subset of the game of this paper. However, not all of these additional assumptions might be meaningful in a real-life scenario. "/>
<outline text="When analysing the small game, all but one additional assumptions may not be acceptable to humans."/>
<outline text="Essentially, the problem is to use game theory, which is a contractual agreement between rational players, to humans who tend to be irrational."/>
<outline text="Suitability of non-strict NE"/>
<outline text="__The attack has no real gain__. A human attacker will not undertake an attack without gain. At the least, if no financial gain could be expected, there would be a psychological satisfaction or thrill that the attacker would expect as benefit. There would be a worry about uncovered risks, not covered by the game theoretical model."/>
<outline text="__There are no costs required for defending__. Only very large organisations with a large budget would be able to afford this luxury."/>
<outline text="__The costs for mounting an attack balance out the resulting benefits__."/>
<outline text="__The defence costs are the same as incurring losses due to an attack__."/>
