<outline text="In this section, following the analysis of the security game $$\mathcal{G}$$ showing the existence of several NE strategies, their relevance as an effective security recommendation to the utility company is discussed."/>
<outline text="Optimal Pure Nash Equilibrium Strategies #h3 ">
    <outline text="To solve this augmented security game, three cases will be considered. This is based on discussing the difference $$\Delta=p_{att_w}-p_{att_s}$$ between the attacker's payoff functions $$p_{att_w}=l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$$ and $$p_{att_s}=l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$." complete="true"/>
    <outline text="Case 1 ($$\Delta&gt;0$$) #h4 " complete="true">
        <outline text="In this case, the existence of a unique pure NE for the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ can be asserted. The corresponding NE strategy is for the utility company to not monitor, and for the attacker to carry out a weak attack. Due to the uniqueness property these solutions are optimal. " complete="true"/>
        <outline text="PROPOSITION 1 #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} &gt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a unique pure Nash Equilibrium strategy of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}) $$ and the corresponding payoffs $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} $$ are optimal. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop1"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="PROOF #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text="First, it needs to be verified that when choosing the pure strategy $$(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}) $$, none of the two players benefit from a unilateral change of pure strategy. #eyo-style:Proof">
                <outline text="Focusing on the utility company, the change of strategy $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ diminishes her payoff since $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} &gt; -c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}-l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w}$$ due to the assumption of a positive monitoring cost. Considering the attacker, the change $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$ is not beneficial because of the main assumption of Case 1. Finally, the change of strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} \rightarrow  s^\mathcal{A}_{-att_s}$$ reduces the payoff due to Assumption #eyo-latex-ref:A3.   Second, a careful inspection of the payoff functions of the remainder of the game, together with the fact that the assumption of Case 1 implies $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} &gt;- c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$ shows that there is no other pure NE equilibrium. This completes the proof. "/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
            <outline text="The value of the optimal payoffs for the UC are $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s}$$ and $$ l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}  $$ for the Attacker. #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="![Diagram](https://www.dropbox.com/s/cn2dksuwqdr8h1k/prop3_arrow.png?dl=1) #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="strategy of the form $$(x^*,y^*) $$ where $$ x^* = \begin{pmatrix}  0 &amp;1\end{pmatrix}$$, $$y^* = \begin{pmatrix}  1&amp; 0&amp; 0\end{pmatrix}^T$$ and the corresponding optimal payoffs are  #wfe-ignore-item "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Case 2 ($$\Delta&lt;0$$) #h4 ">
        <outline text="The result in this case is the existence of a unique pure, non-strict NE under the assumption of an additional condition. \JC{What is a weak NE? What are the optimal actions?}" complete="true"/>
        <outline text="PROPOSITION 2 #wfe-ignore-item " complete="true">
            <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} &lt; l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$ and additionally $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} = c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$ are satisfied \JC{make clear this is a new assumption}, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a pure non-strict Nash Equilibrium strategy of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}) $$ . The corresponding optimal payoffs are $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} $$. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop2"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="PROOF #wfe-ignore-item">
            <outline text="The proof of this proposition is done very similarly to that of Proposition 1 by comparing the changes in payoff, following a unilateral change of strategy.  Focusing first on $$\mathcal{A}$$'s strategy $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$$  and moves to either $$s^\mathcal{A}_{weak} $$ or $$s^\mathcal{A}_{-att} $$, in either case the corresponding payoff will decrease due to the assumption of this case, or Assumption #eyo-latex-ref:A4. Focusing on $$\mathcal{D}$$, if the utility company switches her strategy from $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}$$ to  $$s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ her payoff does not change due to the additional assumption. This proves the existence of the non-strict NE, by definition. Uniqueness can be seen similarly to the previous proposition by inspecting all transitions between payoffs of the game matrix. #eyo-style:Proof" complete="true"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Without the additional assumption, any such change will follow circular paths, hence prohibiting the existence of any pure equilibrium."/>
        <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
            <outline text="![Diagram](https://www.dropbox.com/s/ayuij6h18qsxphz/prop1_arrow.png?dl=1) #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="https://www.draw.io/?state=%7B%22ids%22:%5B%2210U2gnjq-7fWqTlX1H4mf80KUuayRTAns%22%5D,%22action%22:%22open%22,%22userId%22:%22{userId}%22%7D#G10U2gnjq-7fWqTlX1H4mf80KUuayRTAns"/>
            <outline text="We need to verify that none of the two players benefit from unilateral change of pure strategy, when choosing the NE strategy $$(x^*,y^*)$$. "/>
            <outline text="The first result is the existence of a pure, optimal strategy for the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ indicating that the utility company should not monitor and the attacker should do a attectable attack. If both players choose these strategies, their corresponding payoffs will be $$-l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s}$$  for the utility company and $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} $$ for the attacker. "/>
            <outline text="To get this result, we need to add three assumptions that doesn't intefer with the ones we already have. And then, the benefit for a attectable attack is exactly the cost of monitoring and defense $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} = c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$. "/>
            <outline text="However, this would entail a serie of additionnal unilateral strategy changes $$s^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$$ , $$ s^\mathcal{U}_{mon} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon} $$ and finally   $$ s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} \rightarrow s^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Case 3 ($$\Delta=0$$) #h4 " complete="true">
        <outline text="In this last case, one derives the inequality $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}&gt;- c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$ as in Case 1 and obtains a similar but weaker result, as the pure NE is not strict. The proof of the following proposition is omitted and left to the reader."/>
        <outline text="PROPOSITION 3 #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text="If $$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$, the game $$\mathcal{G}$$ admits a unique pure non-strict Nash Equilibrium strategy of the form $$s^*=(s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}, s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}) $$ and the corresponding optimal payoffs are $$s^*_{\mathcal{U}} = -l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} $$ and $$s^*_{\mathcal{A}} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} $$. #eyo-style:Proposition #eyo-latex-label:prop3"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
