                            <outline text="Proposed Security Game #h2 OLD">
<outline text="The proposed security game is a two-player non-zero sum complete information game between the utility company $$\mathcal{U}$$ and the attacker $$\mathcal{A}$$. In a complete information game, parties have full knowledge of the complete set of strategies and corresponding payoffs of all players and the specific selection of actions is based on computing optimal solutions, relying on everyone else proceeding in the same way." complete="true"/>
<outline text="The game is inspired by the Intrusion Detection System (IDS) game of \cite{Alpcan2010} which has been thoroughly analysed in the literature andis well understood. Table \ref{table:game_IDS} illustrates the game where the two strategies available to the defender are to monitor or not, denoted by the strategy space $$S_\mathcal{D} = \{s^\mathcal{D}_{mon},s^\mathcal{D}_{-mon}\}$$, and the attacker chooses between attacking or not attacking: $$S_\mathcal{A} = \{s^\mathcal{A}_{att},s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}\}$$. The positive parameters $$\alpha_c, \alpha_f, \alpha_m, \beta_c$$ and $$\beta_s$$ are used to denote the payoffs corresponding to the various strategies. The main characteristic of this game is the design of the payoff functions in such a way that the monitoring defender only has an incentive to defend in the presence of an attack. The attacker is discouraged from attacking if there is defence in place. This design leads to a circular path when considering payoff-incrementing unilateral changes of strategy, hence prohibiting the existence of a pure Nash Equilibrium." complete="true">
    <outline text="\bgroup \def\arraystretch{1.5} \begin{table}\label{table:game_IDS} \centering \caption{IDS Game of \cite{Alpcan2010} in Normal Form} \begin{tabular}{ c | cc | cc } $\mathcal{D} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow$ &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c} {$s^\mathcal{A}_{att}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c}{$s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}$} \\\hline $s^{\mathcal{D}}_{mon}$ &amp; $\alpha_{c}$, &amp;$- \beta_{c}$ &amp; $-\alpha_{f}$, &amp;$0$\\\hline $s^{\mathcal{D}}_{-mon}$ &amp; $-\alpha_{m}$, &amp;$\beta_{s}$ &amp; $0$, &amp;$0$ \end{tabular} \end{table} \egroup "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Description of Game #h3 ">
    <outline text="In this section, an augmented security game is introduced, extending the IDS game introduced in the previous section by an additional action. The rationale behind this extended game model is twofold: Section \ref{sys_monitor} demonstrated the existence of low-impact attacks which cannot be detected by standard monitoring techniques, and it would be desirable to capture these in a more sophisticated game model. Second, an extended game might better match real-world scenarios and might lead to simpler solutions, in this case pure equilibria rather than mixed ones. " complete="true"/>
    <outline text="STRATEGIES #wfe-ignore-item ">
        <outline text="Section #wfe-latex-ref:vulnerability_section presented three possible monitoring strategies for $$\mathcal{U}$$: to monitor the daily average of forecasting data, to inspect the daily shape of the aggregated forecast, and to inspect the individual forecast data with the same level of detail. In this paper, the assumption is made that the first and second monitoring strategies are most useful in a realistic setting, as they have an observable impact on the strength and outcome of successful attacks while the third monitoring strategy merely eliminates attacks that are possible for weaker monitoring levels. Furthermore, as the data of aggregated forecasts is readily available to the utility company, the first monitoring strategy is not very costly and will be identified with the strategy $$s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}$$. The second monitoring strategy will be denoted as $$ s^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ so that the strategy space for the defender $$\mathcal{U}$$ is as in the previous game $$S_\mathcal{U} = \{s^\mathcal{U}_{mon},s^\mathcal{U}_{-mon}\}$$. The attacker $$\mathcal{A}$$ has three different strategies: to attack strongly with high impact, to perform a weaker attack with low impact, or not to attack at all:  $$S_\mathcal{A} = \{s^\mathcal{A}_{att_s},s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w},s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att}\}$$. " complete="true"/>
        <outline text="\Eckhard{TODO: formulate list below using a paragraph.}">
            <outline text="The following notations for the payoffs for $$\mathcal{U}$$ are introduced: in terms of defence costs, $$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$$ is the cost for monitoring forecast data and $$c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$ the cost for defense. "/>
            <outline text="$$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s}$$ -- the loss resulting from a strong attack (similar, Section XYZ) #item "/>
            <outline text="$$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w}$$ -- the loss resulting from a weak attack (as discussed in Section XYZ) #item "/>
            <outline text="The corresponding payoff functions are:">
                <outline text="$$b^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} $$ -- the benefits from an attack #item "/>
                <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$$ -- the cost for an attack  #item"/>
                <outline text="$$b^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} $$ -- the benefits from a weak attack #item"/>
                <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$$ -- the cost for a weak attack #item"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="GAME #wfe-ignore-item ">
        <outline text="Using these notations, the proposed security game $$\mathcal{G}$$ can be represented in normal form as shown in Table \ref{tab:game_NF}. The monitoring activity always leads to monitoring costs for $$\mathcal{U}$$. If there is no monitoring, $$\mathcal{U}$$ incurs losses $$l_{att_w}^{\mathcal{U}}$$ and $$l_{att_s}^{\mathcal{U}}$$ due to weak and stattacks. Otherwise, despite monitoring, weak attacks cannot be detected, hence there is a resulting loss $$l_{att_w}^{\mathcal{U}}$$. Strong attacks however are detected and mitigated against through some countermeasures, preventing any losses but leading to a defence cost $$c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$$. Finally, if there is no attack, then the only arising non-zero payoff function involved is the monitoring cost for $$\mathcal{U}$$. The attacker $$\mathcal{A}$$ obtains a benefit $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} $$ from a weak attack, but has to invest attack costs $$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} $$. Similarly, the cost $$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} $$ arises from a normal attack, however the model assumes the lack of a benefit for $$\mathcal{A}$$ due to the utility company's defence mechanism. Note that an assumption made in this game is that the benefit of the attacker is the loss of the defender, $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}=l_{att_w}^{\mathcal{U}}$$ and $$b^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}=l_{att_s}^{\mathcal{U}}$$. "/>
        <outline text="TABLE #wfe-ignore-item ">
            <outline text=" \bgroup     \def\arraystretch{1.5}     \begin{table*}\label{tab:game_NF}         \centering         \caption{Security Game in Normal Form}         \begin{tabular}{ c | cc | cc | cc }         $\mathcal{U} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow$ &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c}{$s^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{$s^\mathcal{A}_{att_s}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c}{$s^{\mathcal{A}}_{- att_s}$} \\\hline         $s^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon}$ &amp; $-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} - l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w}$, &amp;$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$ &amp; $-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} -c^\mathcal{U}_{def}$, &amp;$- c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att_s}$ &amp; $-c^\mathcal{U}_{mon}$, &amp;$0$\\\hline         $s^{\mathcal{U}}_{-mon}$ &amp; $-l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w}$, &amp;$l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w} - c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$ &amp; $-l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_s}$, &amp;$l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_s}- c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att_s}$ &amp; $0$, &amp;$0$         \end{tabular}     \end{table*}     \egroup "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Game Assumptions #h3">
    <outline text="\Eckhard{Need to derive these assumptions from IDS Game.}"/>
    <outline text="Adapting the notations from []: #wfe-ignore-outline ">
        <outline text="$$\alpha_c = -c^{\mathcal{U}}_{\mathcal{mon}}-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{def} &lt; 0$$">
            <outline text="Gain from detection: necessary cost to prevent"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\alpha_m={\mathcal{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_s} &gt; 0$$">
            <outline text="lossess if attack occurs and is not mitigated"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\alpha_f=-c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} &lt;0$$ ">
            <outline text="ongoing monitoring cost "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\beta_c=c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att_s} &gt; 0$$ ">
            <outline text="attack effort"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="$$\beta_s={\mathcal{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_s} - c^{\mathcal{A}}_{att_s}$$ ">
            <outline text="benefit from (undetected) attack - attack effort"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Assumption:">
            <outline text="$$-\alpha_m \leq \alpha_c$$ $$\Longleftrightarrow$$ $$c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} + c^{\mathcal{U}}_{def}\leq {\mathcal{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{strong}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Since, in a typical security game, the defender ($$\mathcal{U}$$ in this paper) does not spend more on defence than what they can loose from an attack~\cite{}, the cost of monitoring is assumed to be at the most as high as the losses incurred due to any attack."/>
    <outline text="In particular, this implies for a weak attack">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} \leq l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w}$$ #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A1"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="and that the combined monitoring and defence costs amount to at the most the loss resulting from an attack: ">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} + c^\mathcal{U}_{def} \le l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s}$$.  #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A2"/>
        <outline text="$$-\alpha_m \leq \alpha_c$$ $$\Longleftrightarrow$$ $$c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} + c^{\mathcal{U}}_{def}\leq {\mathcal{l}}^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_s}$$ #wfe-ignore-item "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="A similar principle applies to the attacker: $$\mathcal{A}$$ will not spend more on an attack than the expected gain from it, leading to the assumptions ">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} \leq b^\mathcal{A}_{att_w} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_w}$$ #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A3 "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="and">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} \leq b^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} = l^\mathcal{U}_{att_s}$$. #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A4"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Guided by the experimental results presented in Section #wfe-latex-ref:vulnerability_section, it can also be assumed that the cost for launching an attack is higher than that for a weak attack">
        <outline text="$$c^\mathcal{A}_{att_s} &gt; c^\mathcal{A}_{att_w}$$. #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A5"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Similarly, we assume that an attack leads to higher losses for the utility company: ">
        <outline text="$$l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_s}&gt;l^{\mathcal{U}}_{att_w}$$. #wfe-style:Equation #wfe-style:Equation #eyo-latex-label:A6"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="The suitability of a game theoretical model depends not only on whether provided strategies are realistic and reasonably complete to capture all possible actions, but also whether there are &quot;meaningful&quot; solutions which are acceptable to all players. #wfe-ignore-item "/>
    <outline text="The security game with two actions exhibits the same lack of pure NE strategies as the game []. While this indicates that the concept of mixed strategies is useful in this scenario, and a stronger concept as it will compute optimal strategies, it has also drawbacks. Game theory has been criticised in the past due to the difficulty of interpreting mixed solutions in the real world []. "/>
    <outline text="Alternative notation, using bimatrix game matrices #wfe-ignore-outline ">
        <outline text="$$ A = \begin{pmatrix}   -c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} - l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} &amp; -c^{\mathcal{U}}_{mon} -c^\mathcal{U}_{def} &amp; -c^\mathcal{U}_{mon} \\    -l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} &amp; -l^{\mathcal{U}}_{det} &amp; 0\end{pmatrix}$$"/>
        <outline text="$$ B = \begin{pmatrix}  l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} - c^\mathcal{A}_{udet} &amp;  - c^{\mathcal{A}}_{det} &amp; 0\\  l^\mathcal{U}_{udet} - c^\mathcal{A}_{udet}  &amp; l^{\mathcal{U}}_{det}- c^{\mathcal{A}}_{det} &amp;0 \end{pmatrix}$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
